990\n|-\n|[[John Siddons]]\n| Victoria\n|1981\u20131983; 1985\u20131986 (1987)<ref group=\"n\" name=\"note2\">Resigned from party in November 1986 and sat as an independent senator until defeat at the 1987 election as a Unite Australia Party candidate.</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jack Evans (Australian politician)|Jack Evans]]\n| Western Australia\n|1983\u20131985\n|-\n|[[David Vigor]]\n| South Australia\n|1985\u20131987<ref group=\"n\" name=\"note2\" />\n|-\n|[[Norm Sanders]]\n| Tasmania\n|1985\u20131990\n|-\n|[[Janet Powell]]\n| Victoria\n|1986\u20131992 (1993)<ref group=\"n\">Resigned from party in July 1992 and sat as an independent senator until defeat at the 1993 election.</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Coulter (politician)|John Coulter]]\n|South Australia\n|1987\u20131995\n|-\n|[[Paul McLean (politician)|Paul McLean]]\n| New South Wales\n|1987\u20131991\n|-\n|[[Jean Jenkins (politician)|Jean Jenkins]]\n| Western Australia\n|1987\u20131990\n|-\n|[[Vicki Bourne]]\n| New South Wales\n|1990\u20132002\n|-\n|[[Sid Spindler]]\n| Victoria\n|1990\u20131996\n|-\n|[[Cheryl Kernot]]\n| Queensland\n|1990\u20131997\n|-\n|[[Robert Bell (Australian politician)|Robert Bell]]\n| Tasmania\n|1990\u20131996\n|-\n|[[Karin Sowada]]\n| New South Wales\n|1991\u20131993\n|-\n|[[John Woodley]]\n| Queensland\n|1993\u20132001\n|-\n|[[Meg Lees]]\n| South Australia\n|1990\u20132002 (2005)<ref group=\"n\">Resigned from party in July 2002 and sat as an independent senator until defeat at the 2004 election as an Australian Progressive Alliance candidate.</ref>\n|-\n|[[Natasha Stott Despoja]]\n| South Australia\n|1995\u20132008\n|-\n|[[Lyn Allison]]\n| Victoria\n|1996\u20132008\n|-\n|[[Andrew Murray (Australian politician)|Andrew Murray]]\n| Western Australia\n|1996\u20132008\n|-\n|[[Andrew Bartlett]]\n| Queensland\n|1997\u20132008\n|-\n|[[Aden Ridgeway]]\n| New South Wales\n|1999\u20132005\n|-\n|[[Brian Greig]]\n| Western Australia\n|1999\u20132005\n|-\n|[[John Cherry (Australian politician)|John Cherry]]\n| Queensland\n|2001\u20132005\n|}\n\n===State and territory members===\n====Australian Capital Territory====\n*1979\u20131985: [[Ivor Vivian]], member of the [[Australian Capital Territory House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]\n*1979\u20131985: [[Gordon Walsh]], member of the House of Assembly\n*2001\u20132004: [[Roslyn Dundas]], member of the [[Australian Capital Territory Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]]\n\n====New South Wales====\n*1981\u20131998: [[Elisabeth Kirkby]], member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council|Legislative Council]]\n*1988\u20131996: [[Richard Jones (New South Wales politician, born 1940)|Richard Jones]], member of the Legislative Council<ref group=\"n\">Resigned from party in 1996 and sat as an independent MLC until retirement at the 2003 election.</ref>\n*1998\u20132007: [[Arthur Chesterfield-Evans]], member of the Legislative Council\n\n====South Australia====\n*1977\u20131982: [[Robin Millhouse]], member of the [[South Australian House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]\n*1979\u20131985: [[Lance Milne]], member of the [[South Australian Legislative Council|Legislative Council]]\n*1982: [[Heather Southcott]], member of the House of Assembly\n*1982\u20131993, 1997\u20132006: [[Ian Gilfillan]], member of the Legislative Council\n*1985\u20132003: [[Mike Elliott (politician)|Mike Elliott]], member of the Legislative Council\n*1993\u20132009: [[Sandra Kanck]], member of the Legislative Council\n*2003\u20132006: [[Kate Reynolds]], member of the Legislative Council\n*2009: [[David Winderlich]], member of the Legislative Council<ref group=\"n\">Resigned from party on 7 October 2009 and sat as an independent MLC until 2010 election when was not re-elected.</ref>\n\n====Tasmania====\n*1980\u20131982: [[Norm Sanders]], member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]\n\n====Western Australia====\n*1997\u20132001: [[Helen Hodgson]], member of the [[Western Australian Legislative Council|Legislative Council]]\n*1997\u20132001: [[Norm Kelly (Australian politician)|Norm Kelly]], member of the Legislative Council\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Australian Democrats}}\n*[[Social liberalism]]\n*[[Liberalism worldwide]]\n*[[List of liberal parties]]\n*[[Liberal democracy]]\n*[[Timeline of (small-l) liberal parties in Australia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Bennett D, [http://www.pwhce.org/discord.html Discord in the Democrats] PWHCE article, Melbourne 2002\n*''Beyond Our Expectations''\u2014Proceedings of the Australian Democrats First National Conference, Canberra, 16\u201317 February 1980. [Papers by: Don Chipp, Sir Mark Oliphant, Prof. Stephen Boyden, Bob Whan, Julian Cribb, Colin Mason, John Siddons, A. McDonald]\n*Chipp D (ed. Larkin J) ''Chipp'', Methuen Haynes, North Ryde NSW, 1987 {{ISBN|0-454-01345-0}}\n*Gauja A ''[http://pa.oxfordjournals.org/content/63/3/486.short?rss=1 Evaluating the Success and Contribution of a Minor Party: the Case of the Australian Democrats]'' [[Parliamentary Affairs]] (2010) 63(3): 486\u2013503, 21 January 2010, at [[Oxford Journals]]. (Paid subscription, [[Athens (access and identity management service)|Athens]] or participating library membership required)\n*Madden C [http://www.aph.gov.au/binaries/library/pubs/rp/2008-09/09rp25.pdf ''Australian Democrats: the passing of an era''], Research Paper, Parliamentary Library\n*Paul A and Miller L ''The Third Team'' July 2007 A historical essay in ''30 Years\u2014Australian Democrats'' Melbourne 2007. (A 72-page anthology of historical and biographical monographs about the state and federal parliamentary experiences of the Democrats, for the party's 30th anniversary.)\n*Sugita H ''Challenging 'twopartism'\u2014the contribution of the Australian Democrats to the Australian party system'', PhD thesis, Flinders University of South Australia, July 1995\n*Warhurst J (ed.) ''Keeping the bastards honest'' Allen & Unwin Sydney 1997 {{ISBN|1-86448-420-9}}\n*Warhurst J, [https://web.archive.org/web/20071128142344/http://australianpolitics.com/words/2006/archives/00000254.shtml ''Don Chipp Was The Right Man In The Right Place At The Right Time''] ''Canberra Times'' 7 September 2006\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.australian-democrats.org.au}}\n\n{{Political parties in Australia}}\n{{Defunct Australian political parties}}\n{{New South Wales political parties}}\n\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Centrist parties in Australia]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 2015]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2019]]\n[[Category:Social liberal parties]]\n", "name_user": "Adpete", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDecline:fix own grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Democrats"}
{"title_page": "Ottawa station", "text_new": "{{short description|Primary intercity train station in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada operated by VIA Rail}}\n{{other}}\n{{Infobox station\n | name          = Ottawa\n | style         = Via Rail\n | image         = Ottawa Train Station.JPG\n | image_caption =\n | address       = 200 Tremblay Road<br />[[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]<br />K1G 3H5\n | coordinates   = {{coord|45|24|59|N|75|39|06|W|region:CA-ON_type:railwaystation|display=inline,title}}\n | line          = {{rint|ca|rail}} [[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]] <!-- detailed line information under \"services\" -->\n | connections   = {{rint|ottawa|otrain|1}} [[Tremblay station|Tremblay]]\n | structure     = At-grade\n | platform      = 5 low-level [[island platform]]s\n | tracks        = 6\n | parking       = Surface Lot (Operator: Park Indigo)\n | bicycle       =\n | baggage_check =\n | opened        = August 1, 1966\n | architect     = [[John B. Parkin|John B. Parkin & Associates]]\n | architectural_style = [[International Style (architecture)|International]]\n | closed        =\n | rebuilt       =\n | electrified   = No\n | ADA           = Yes\n | code          = Via Rail: [http://www.viarail.ca/cgi-bin/genericXSLT?xml=OTTW.xml&xsl=en_station.xsl OTTW]<br>[[IATA]]: [http://theairdb.com/airport/XDS.html XDS]\n | owned         = [[Via Rail]]\n | zone          =\n | former        = \n | passengers    =\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | mpassengers   =\n | services      = {{Adjacent stations|system1=Via Rail\n|line1=Toronto-Ottawa|left1=Fallowfield\n|line2=Fallowfield-Montreal|right2=Casselman\n|line3=Fallowfield-Montreal|left3=Fallowfield|to-left3=Fallowfield|note-left3=Limited service|right3=Casselman\n|line4=Ottawa-Qu\u00e9bec City|right4=Casselman\n}}\n | map_locator   =\n| embedded={{designation list|embed=yes|designation1=HRSC|designation1_offname=Ottawa Railway Station|designation1_date=June 1, 1996|designation1_number =[http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15815 15815]}}\n}}\n[[File:CorridorVia.svg|thumb|[[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Via Rail Corridor]] Route Map]]\n[[File:Ottawa train station 2013 2.jpg|thumb|Ottawa station main entrance in 2013]]\n[[File:Ottawa Train Station, 2017 (20170814 171059).jpg|thumb|Ottawa station waiting area, 2017]]\n[[File:Waiting in line at Ottawa Station.jpg|thumb|Waiting in line at Ottawa station]]\n[[File:Ottawa train station 2013 1.jpg|thumb|Station platforms in 2013]]\n'''Ottawa station''' ([[International Air Transport Association airport code|IATA]]: XDS), or '''Ottawa Train Station''', is an inter-city train station in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] operated by [[Via Rail]]. It is located 4 km to the east of [[downtown Ottawa]] in the [[Eastway Gardens]] neighbourhood and serves inter-city trains connecting to [[Toronto]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] and [[Montreal]] on Via Rail's [[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]] Route. \n\n==Location==\nOttawa station is located at '''200 [[Tremblay Road]]''', which lies directly south of [[Ontario Highway 417]] (known locally as the ''Queensway'') near Exit 117 and east of [[Riverside Drive (Ottawa)|Riverside Drive (Regional Road 19)]] in an industrial park area. Its main entrance faces north to Tremblay Road. \n\nSouth of the station building, trains call at 5 low-level [[island platform]]s and 6 tracks. The platforms are connected to the main building by an underground walkway that is accessed by a circular ramp and escalators. The tracks are bordered on the south by Terminal Avenue.\n\n[[RCGT Park]], a minor-league baseball stadium is located north of both Tremblay Road and Highway 417 and is accessible by the Max Keeping Pedestrian Bridge. The station is also within the vicinity of a number of big box stores, including the Ottawa Train Yards shopping complex south of Terminal Avenue. (However there is no pedestrian bridge over the tracks, so this can only be accessed on foot or by car via Belfast Road.) An office complex of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is located to the north east of the station, across the highway cloverleaf and next to the [[Rideau River]].\n\n==Services==\nThe station is staffed and offers ticket sales, checked baggage and checkroom service, bicycle box service, an ATM, a restaurant, vending machines, wifi (in the station and business lounge), telephones and washrooms.\n\nOttawa Station is also linked to local public transportation by [[OC Transpo]]'s [[Tremblay station|Tremblay LRT Station]] north of the main entrance. Located on the [[Confederation Line]], trains travel west to [[downtown Ottawa]] (stopping at [[Rideau station]], [[Parliament station]] and [[Lyon station]]) and east in the direction of the [[Blair station]] terminus.\n\nA taxi stand is located outside the main entrance and short-term parking lots operated by Park Indigo are available on the east and west sides of the station. A Discount Car & Truck Rentals kiosk is also located north of the station. \n\nThe station is wheelchair accessible including the ticket office, washrooms and trains. Wheelchairs, an elevator and a wheelchair lift are available.\n\n==Structure==\nOttawa station is an international style building composed of exposed cantilevered [[Truss#Vierendeel truss|Vierendeel trusses]] supported by massive concrete [[Pier (architecture)|piers]]. This creates a spacious [[open plan]] interior with a powerful roofline. The station's walls are a non-loadbearing glass skin and extend through the open steel trusses to the roof deck. None of the interior walls extend above the lower chords of the trusses, allowing for an uninterrupted view of the roof structure.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706192640/http://www.orsa.ca/resources/gallery/details.asp?id=18\"|title=Ottawa Train Station  |author=Ottawa Regional Society of Architects |date= |website=www.orsa.ca}}</ref>\n\nInside, an expansive waiting area features a circular ticket office and a descending circular ramp leading to the far [[railway platform|platforms]].\n\n==History==\nThe station was designed by [[John B. Parkin|John B. Parkin & Associates]] and was built in 1966. It won a [[Governor General's Award|Massey Medal]] for architecture in 1967. In 2000, the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] named the station as one of the top 500 buildings produced in Canada during the last millennium.<ref name=\"RAIC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ty-a.ca/Citizen/top500.htm|title=Cultural consequence|last=Cook|first=Maria|work=Ottawa Citizen|publisher=Canwest|date=11 May 2000|accessdate=11 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530090211/http://www.ty-a.ca/Citizen/top500.htm|archivedate=30 May 2010}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Union Station Ottawa a034379.jpg|thumb|Ottawa's former Union Station in the 1920s]]\nOttawa's trains once came into the large downtown [[Senate of Canada Building|Union Station]] (active 1912\u20131966), a short distance from the [[Parliament Hill|Parliament buildings]] and south of the [[Ch\u00e2teau Laurier]] Hotel. However, in 1966 the railway tracks beside the [[Rideau Canal]] were replaced by the [[National Capital Commission]]\u2019s [[Colonel By Drive]] scenic parkway as part of an [[Greber Plan|urban renewal plan]]. Initially the former station was converted into a [[Government Conference Centre]] before becoming a new temporary home for the [[Senate of Canada]] in 2019, as extensive renovations are conducted on their former location in the [[Centre Block]] building on [[Parliament Hill]].\n\nPer a sign located inside the station: <blockquote>\"The Ottawa Station was completed in 1966 as part of a plan for the relocation and consolidation of many railway lines built between 1854 and 1916. The new arrangement was based on the [[Greber Plan|plans]] of the noted urban planner, [[Jacques Greber]], and was constructed by the [[National Capital Commission]]. The [[Canadian National Railway]] and the [[Canadian Pacific railway]] are owners and operators of the new installations.\" <ref>{{Cite sign |title=Ottawa Station |year= |type=Plaque inside station|publisher=|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/66151649@N02/38684882361/in/dateposted-ff/ |location=Ottawa}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe station has been protected under the [[Heritage Railway Stations Protection Act]] since 1996.  It \"is a glass and steel, International style railway station [...] The VIA Rail Station at Ottawa is one of the finest examples of the [[International Style (architecture)|International style]] in Canadian architecture.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15815&pid=0 |title=VIA Rail Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= historic places.ca|publisher= |access-date=November 17, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe station was previously served by OC Transpo [[Bus rapid transit]] at an adjacent [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] station known as Train Station. With the construction of the [[Confederation Line]] the bus rapid transit system was converted to rail, the station renamed [[Tremblay station]] and light rail service commenced on September 14, 2019. \n\n==Renovations==\nA $21.7 million renovation project started late 2016. The project will add an elevator in the spiral ramp and at track 3 and 4, a high-level platform for track 1, and roof improvements.<ref>http://www.viarail.ca/en/about-via-rail/media-room/latest-news/213601/29-september-2016-celebrating-50-years-via-rail-ottawa-</ref>\n\n==Other Connections==\n[[Air France\u2013KLM]] runs a connecting shuttle bus from this station to [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport]], exclusive for the airline's customers only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.klm.com/travel/ca_en/plan_and_book/ticket_information/travel_by_train_on_a_klm_ticket/index.htm#p2 |title=Bus between Ottawa Railway Station (XDS) and Montreal (YUL) |work=Travel by train on a KLM ticket |publisher=KLM |accessdate=December 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206063215/http://www.klm.com/travel/ca_en/plan_and_book/ticket_information/travel_by_train_on_a_klm_ticket/index.htm#p2 |archivedate=2015-12-06 }}</ref> As of 2016, Air France\u2013KLM has three daily bus services between those cities.<ref name=AFQuebec>\"[http://corporate.airfrance.com/en/press/press-releases/article/item/a-new-bus-service-to-quebec-city-1/ A new bus service to Quebec City] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220045248/http://corporate.airfrance.com/en/press/press-releases/article/item/a-new-bus-service-to-quebec-city-1/ |date=2017-02-20 }}.\" [[Air France]]. August 16, 2016. Retrieved on October 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n[[Swiss International Air Lines]] previously operated its Swissbus service from Ottawa station to Dorval Airport for Swiss customers.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20120620154627/http://www.swiss.com/countries/CA/en/local_content/news/Pages/swissbus_ottawa.aspx Swissbus  Bus transportation between Ottawa and Montreal-Trudeau airport]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6lbrwC9Sb?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20120620154627/http://www.swiss.com/countries/CA/en/local_content/news/Pages/swissbus_ottawa.aspx Archive]). [[Swiss International Air Lines]]. June 20, 2012. Retrieved on October 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Ottawa Train Station}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706192640/http://www.orsa.ca/resources/gallery/details.asp?id=18 Ottawa Regional Society of Architects -- Architecture of the Ottawa Train Station]\n*[http://madhava.com/photo/christmas2004/2004_12_27/ Photos of Ottawa Train Station]\n*{{Via Station|OTTW}}\n\n{{Ottawa landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Via Rail stations in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1966]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1966]]\n[[Category:Designated Heritage Railway Stations in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Primary intercity train station in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada operated by VIA Rail}}\n{{other}}\n{{Infobox station\n | name          = Ottawa\n | style         = Via Rail\n | image         = Ottawa Train Station.JPG\n | image_caption =\n | address       = 200 Tremblay Road<br />[[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]<br />K1G 3H5\n | coordinates   = {{coord|45|24|59|N|75|39|06|W|region:CA-ON_type:railwaystation|display=inline,title}}\n | line          = {{rint|ca|rail}} [[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]] <!-- detailed line information under \"services\" -->\n | connections   = {{rint|ottawa|otrain|1}} [[Tremblay station|Tremblay]]\n | structure     = At-grade\n | platform      = 5 low-level [[island platform]]s\n | tracks        = 6\n | parking       = Surface Lot (Operator: Park Indigo)\n | bicycle       =\n | baggage_check =\n | opened        = August 1, 1966\n | architect     = [[John B. Parkin|John B. Parkin & Associates]]\n | architectural_style = [[International Style (architecture)|International]]\n | closed        =\n | rebuilt       =\n | electrified   = No\n | ADA           = Yes\n | code          = Via Rail: [http://www.viarail.ca/cgi-bin/genericXSLT?xml=OTTW.xml&xsl=en_station.xsl OTTW]<br>[[IATA]]: [http://theairdb.com/airport/XDS.html XDS]\n | owned         = [[Via Rail]]\n | zone          =\n | former        = \n | passengers    =\n | pass_year     =\n | pass_percent  =\n | pass_system   =\n | mpassengers   =\n | services      = {{Adjacent stations|system1=Via Rail\n|line1=Toronto-Ottawa|left1=Fallowfield\n|line2=Fallowfield-Montreal|right2=Casselman\n|line3=Fallowfield-Montreal|left3=Fallowfield|to-left3=Fallowfield|note-left3=Limited service|right3=Casselman\n|line4=Ottawa-Qu\u00e9bec City|right4=Casselman\n}}\n | map_locator   =\n| embedded={{designation list|embed=yes|designation1=HRSC|designation1_offname=Ottawa Railway Station|designation1_date=June 1, 1996|designation1_number =[http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15815 15815]}}\n}}\n[[File:CorridorVia.svg|thumb|[[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Via Rail Corridor]] Route Map]]\n[[File:Ottawa train station 2013 2.jpg|thumb|Ottawa station main entrance in 2013]]\n[[File:Ottawa Train Station, 2017 (20170814 171059).jpg|thumb|Ottawa station waiting area, 2017]]\n[[File:Waiting in line at Ottawa Station.jpg|thumb|Waiting in line at Ottawa station]]\n[[File:Ottawa train station 2013 1.jpg|thumb|Station platforms in 2013]]\n'''Ottawa station''' ([[International Air Transport Association airport code|IATA]]: XDS), or '''Ottawa Train Station''', is an inter-city train station in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] operated by [[Via Rail]]. It is located 4 km to the east of [[downtown Ottawa]] in the [[Eastway Gardens]] neighbourhood and serves inter-city trains connecting to [[Toronto]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] and [[Montreal]] on Via Rail's [[Qu\u00e9bec City\u2013Windsor Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]] Route. \n\n==Location==\nOttawa station is located at '''200 [[Tremblay Road]]''', which lies directly south of [[Ontario Highway 417]] (known locally as the ''Queensway'') near Exit 117 and east of [[Riverside Drive (Ottawa)|Riverside Drive (Regional Road 19)]] in an industrial park area. Its main entrance faces north to Tremblay Road. \n\nSouth of the station building, trains call at 5 low-level [[island platform]]s and 6 tracks. The platforms are connected to the main building by an underground walkway that is accessed by a circular ramp and escalators. The tracks are bordered on the south by Terminal Avenue.\n\n[[RCGT Park]], a minor-league baseball stadium is located north of both Tremblay Road and Highway 417 and is accessible by the Max Keeping Pedestrian Bridge. The station is also within the vicinity of a number of big box stores, including the Ottawa Train Yards shopping complex south of Terminal Avenue. (However there is no pedestrian bridge over the tracks, so this can only be accessed on foot or by car via Belfast Road.) An office complex of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is located to the north east of the station, across the highway cloverleaf and next to the [[Rideau River]].\n\n==Services==\nThe station is staffed and offers ticket sales, checked baggage and checkroom service, bicycle box service, an ATM, a restaurant, vending machines, wifi (in the station and business lounge), telephones and washrooms.\n\nOttawa Station is also linked to local public transportation by [[OC Transpo]]'s [[Tremblay station|Tremblay LRT Station]] north of the main entrance. Located on the [[Confederation Line]], trains travel west to [[downtown Ottawa]] (stopping at [[Rideau station]], [[Parliament station]] and [[Lyon station]]) and east in the direction of the [[Blair station]] terminus.\n\nA taxi stand is located outside the main entrance and short-term parking lots operated by Park Indigo are available on the east and west sides of the station. A Discount Car & Truck Rentals kiosk is also located north of the station. \n\nThe station is wheelchair accessible including the ticket office, washrooms and trains. Wheelchairs, an elevator and a wheelchair lift are available.\n\n==Structure==\nOttawa station is an international style building composed of exposed cantilevered [[Truss#Vierendeel truss|Vierendeel trusses]] supported by massive concrete [[Pier (architecture)|piers]]. This creates a spacious [[open plan]] interior with a powerful roofline. The station's walls are a non-loadbearing glass skin and extend through the open steel trusses to the roof deck. None of the interior walls extend above the lower chords of the trusses, allowing for an uninterrupted view of the roof structure.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706192640/http://www.orsa.ca/resources/gallery/details.asp?id=18\"|title=Ottawa Train Station  |author=Ottawa Regional Society of Architects |date= |website=www.orsa.ca}}</ref>\n\nInside, an expansive waiting area features a circular ticket office and a descending circular ramp leading to the far [[railway platform|platforms]].\n\n==History==\nThe station was designed by [[John B. Parkin|John B. Parkin & Associates]] and was built in 1966. It won a [[Governor General's Award|Massey Medal]] for architecture in 1967. In 2000, the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] named the station as one of the top 500 buildings produced in Canada during the last millennium.<ref name=\"RAIC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ty-a.ca/Citizen/top500.htm|title=Cultural consequence|last=Cook|first=Maria|work=Ottawa Citizen|publisher=Canwest|date=11 May 2000|accessdate=11 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530090211/http://www.ty-a.ca/Citizen/top500.htm|archivedate=30 May 2010}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Union Station Ottawa a034379.jpg|thumb|Ottawa's former Union Station in the 1920s]]\nOttawa's trains once came into the large downtown [[Senate of Canada Building|Union Station]] (active 1912\u20131966), a short distance from the [[Parliament Hill|Parliament buildings]] and south of the [[Ch\u00e2teau Laurier]] Hotel. However, in 1966 the railway tracks beside the [[Rideau Canal]] were replaced by the [[National Capital Commission]]\u2019s [[Colonel By Drive]] scenic parkway as part of an [[Greber Plan|urban renewal plan]]. Initially the former station was converted into a [[Government Conference Centre]] before becoming a new temporary home for the [[Senate of Canada]] in 2019, as extensive renovations are conducted on their former location in the [[Centre Block]] building on [[Parliament Hill]].\n\nPer a sign located inside the station: <blockquote>\"The Ottawa Station was completed in 1966 as part of a plan for the relocation and consolidation of many railway lines built between 1854 and 1916. The new arrangement was based on the [[Greber Plan|plans]] of the noted urban planner, [[Jacques Greber]], and was constructed by the [[National Capital Commission]]. The [[Canadian National Railway]] and the [[Canadian Pacific railway]] are owners and operators of the new installations.\" <ref>{{Cite sign |title=Ottawa Station |year= |type=Plaque inside station|publisher=|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/66151649@N02/38684882361/in/dateposted-ff/ |location=Ottawa}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe station has been protected under the [[Heritage Railway Stations Protection Act]] since 1996.  It \"is a glass and steel, International style railway station [...] The VIA Rail Station at Ottawa is one of the finest examples of the [[International style]] in Canadian architecture.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15815&pid=0 |title=VIA Rail Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= historic places.ca|publisher= |access-date=November 17, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe station was previously served by OC Transpo [[Bus rapid transit]] at an adjacent [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] station known as Train Station. With the construction of the [[Confederation Line]] the bus rapid transit system was converted to rail, the station renamed [[Tremblay station]] and light rail service commenced on September 14, 2019. \n\n==Renovations==\nA $21.7 million renovation project started late 2016. The project will add an elevator in the spiral ramp and at track 3 and 4, a high-level platform for track 1, and roof improvements.<ref>http://www.viarail.ca/en/about-via-rail/media-room/latest-news/213601/29-september-2016-celebrating-50-years-via-rail-ottawa-</ref>\n\n==Other Connections==\n[[Air France\u2013KLM]] runs a connecting shuttle bus from this station to [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport]], exclusive for the airline's customers only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.klm.com/travel/ca_en/plan_and_book/ticket_information/travel_by_train_on_a_klm_ticket/index.htm#p2 |title=Bus between Ottawa Railway Station (XDS) and Montreal (YUL) |work=Travel by train on a KLM ticket |publisher=KLM |accessdate=December 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206063215/http://www.klm.com/travel/ca_en/plan_and_book/ticket_information/travel_by_train_on_a_klm_ticket/index.htm#p2 |archivedate=2015-12-06 }}</ref> As of 2016, Air France\u2013KLM has three daily bus services between those cities.<ref name=AFQuebec>\"[http://corporate.airfrance.com/en/press/press-releases/article/item/a-new-bus-service-to-quebec-city-1/ A new bus service to Quebec City] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220045248/http://corporate.airfrance.com/en/press/press-releases/article/item/a-new-bus-service-to-quebec-city-1/ |date=2017-02-20 }}.\" [[Air France]]. August 16, 2016. Retrieved on October 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n[[Swiss International Air Lines]] previously operated its Swissbus service from Ottawa station to Dorval Airport for Swiss customers.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20120620154627/http://www.swiss.com/countries/CA/en/local_content/news/Pages/swissbus_ottawa.aspx Swissbus  Bus transportation between Ottawa and Montreal-Trudeau airport]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6lbrwC9Sb?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20120620154627/http://www.swiss.com/countries/CA/en/local_content/news/Pages/swissbus_ottawa.aspx Archive]). [[Swiss International Air Lines]]. June 20, 2012. Retrieved on October 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Ottawa Train Station}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706192640/http://www.orsa.ca/resources/gallery/details.asp?id=18 Ottawa Regional Society of Architects -- Architecture of the Ottawa Train Station]\n*[http://madhava.com/photo/christmas2004/2004_12_27/ Photos of Ottawa Train Station]\n*{{Via Station|OTTW}}\n\n{{Ottawa landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Via Rail stations in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1966]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1966]]\n[[Category:Designated Heritage Railway Stations in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:International style\u2192International Style (architecture)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottawa_station"}
{"title_page": "Doom (2016 video game)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Doom\n| image = Doom Cover.jpg\n| developer = [[id Software]]{{efn|Additional work for Nintendo Switch by [[Panic Button (company)|Panic Button]].}}\n| publisher = [[Bethesda Softworks]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|[[Marty Stratton]]|Hugo Martin}}\n| producer = Timothy Bell\n| programmer = Billy Ethan Khan\n| writer = Adam Gascoine\n| composer = [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]]\n| series = ''[[Doom (franchise)|Doom]]''\n| engine = [[id Tech 6]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]|[[Google Stadia|Stadia]]}}\n| released = {{Unbulleted list|'''Windows''', '''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''|May 13, 2016|'''Nintendo Switch'''|November 10, 2017}}\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Doom''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] video game developed by [[id Software]] and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]]. It was released worldwide on [[Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] in May 2016 and is powered by [[id Tech 6]]. A port for [[Nintendo Switch]] was co-developed with [[Panic Button (company)|Panic Button]] and released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stevivor.com/news/doom-on-switch-runs-at-30-fps-has-9gb-multiplayer-download/|title=DOOM on Switch runs at 30 FPS, has 9GB multiplayer download|publisher=Stevivor}}</ref> A reboot of the [[Doom (franchise)|''Doom'' franchise]], it is the fourth title in the main series and the first major installment since ''[[Doom 3]]'' in 2004.\n\n''Doom'' was announced as \"''Doom 4''\" in 2008, and that version underwent an extensive development cycle with different builds and designs before the game was restarted in 2011 and revealed as simply \"''Doom''\" in 2014. It was tested by customers who pre-ordered the 2014 Bethesda game ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'' and also by the general public. [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]] composed the music for the game, with additional music contributed by Ben F. Carney, Chris Hite, and Chad Mossholder.\n\nPlayers take the role of an [[Doomguy|unnamed space marine]] as he battles demonic forces from [[Hell]] that have been unleashed by the Union Aerospace Corporation on a future-set colonized planet [[Mars]]. The gameplay returns to a faster pace with more open-ended levels, closer to the first two games than the slower [[survival horror]] approach of ''Doom 3''. It also features environment traversal, character upgrades, and the ability to perform executions known as \"glory kills\". The game also supports an online multiplayer component and a level editor known as \"SnapMap\", co-developed with [[Certain Affinity]]{{efn|[[BattleCry Studios]] has since taken over Certain Affinity's development duties.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Mike|title=BattleCry devs now working with id on Doom multiplayer|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/443533/BattleCry+devs+now+working+with+id+on+Doom+multiplayer/|website=www.gamereactor.eu|publisher=[[Gamereactor]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>}} and [[Escalation Studios]], respectively.\n\n''Doom'' was well-received by critics and players. The single-player campaign, graphics, soundtrack, and gameplay received considerable praise, with reviewers crediting the game for recapturing the spirit of the classic ''Doom'' games and first-person shooters of the 1990s, whereas the multiplayer mode drew the most significant criticism. It was the second best-selling video game in North America and the UK a few weeks after its release and sold over 500,000 copies for PCs within the same time period. A sequel titled ''[[Doom Eternal]]'' was announced at [[E3 2018]] for Nintendo Switch, Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One and [[Google Stadia|Stadia]] and was released on March 20, 2020, with the Nintendo Switch port coming later in 2020.\n\n==Gameplay==\n\n===Single-player===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Output OK1Cm5.gif|thumb|left|250px|An animation of the [[Doom Slayer]] sawing two Imps, and the player gaining ammunition]] -->\n\nAccording to the game's executive producer [[Marty Stratton]], the key principles of ''Doom''{{'}}s single-player mode are \"badass demons, big effing guns, and moving really fast\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/hands-on-dooms-coolest-new-gun-is-powered-by-sprinting/|title=Hands-on: ''Doom''{{'}}s coolest new gun is powered by sprinting|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2016|first=Ian|last=Birnbaum|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> The game allows players to perform movements such as double jumps and ledge climbs throughout levels of industrial and corporate fields of a Union Aerospace Corporation (UAC) research facility on [[Mars]] and then levels of Hell,<ref name=gi-gruesome>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/11/video-the-gruesome-art-design-of-doom.aspx|title=The Gruesome Level Design Of ''Doom''|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 11, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> as the combat system puts emphasis upon momentum and speed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-revealed-at-quakecon-2014-and-heres-what-we-saw/|title=Doom revealed at QuakeCon 2014, and here's what we saw|first=Ian|last= Birnbaum |date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> The approach is known as \"push-forward combat\", which discourages players from taking cover behind obstacles or [[Health (games)#Regenerating health|resting to regain health]] while playing from the [[Doom Slayer]] 's perspective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/08/06/doom-cant-afford-to-let-you-hang-back/|title=''DOOM'' can\u2019t afford to let you hang back|first=Sherif|last=Saed|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> Players instead collect health and armor pick-ups by killing enemies. \"Glory Kills\" is a newly-introduced melee execution system; when enough damage has been dealt to an enemy, the game will highlight it and allow the player to perform a quick and violent melee takedown, rewarding the player with small health recovery.<ref name=glory-kills/>\n\nThe fights also require the player to develop simple tactics. As the game gets harder, the player needs to use the advantages of fight arenas and their bonuses smarter. They also need to decide which enemy has to be killed firstly and how to move on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Davenport|first=James|date=May 18, 2016|website=PC Gamer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/5/18/11706108/doom-review-PC-xbox-one-PS4|title=Doom Review|last=Gies|first=Arthur|date=May 18, 2016|website=Polygon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-6416432/|title=Doom Review|last=Brown|first=Peter|date=May 17, 2016|website=Gamespot|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game features a large arsenal of weapons which can be collected and freely switched by players throughout the game and require no reloading. Recurring weapons of the series also make a return, including the super shotgun and [[BFG (weapon)|BFG 9000]]. The BFG has a very small ammunition capacity, but is extremely powerful. Similarly, the chainsaw returns, but has been reintroduced as a special-use weapon<ref name=gr-doom-development/> that relies upon fuel, but can be used to instantly cut through enemies and provide a greater-than-normal drop of ammunition for the player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/20/the-explosive-modified-arsenal-of-doom.aspx|title=The Explosive, Modified Arsenal of ''Doom''|first=Matt|last=Bertz|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany enemies also return from the original game, such as the Revenant, Pinky, Mancubus, and [[Cyberdemon]], with many also redesigned.<ref name=gr-doom-development>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-4-review/?|title=Doom is fast, thrilling, authentic, and deeply, hilariously gory|first=David|last=Houghton |date=July 3, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[GamesRadar]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707074519/http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-4-review/|archivedate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> ''Doom''{{'}}s campaign was made to be at least 13 hours long, and the \"Ultra-Nightmare\" difficulty level features [[permadeath]], which causes the savegame to be lost once the player dies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dooms-campaign-is-about-13-hours-dev-says/1100-6434816/|title=Doom's Campaign Is About 13 Hours, Dev Says|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|publisher=GameSpot|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ign.com/articles/2016/04/28/nobody-has-beaten-dooms-hardest-difficulty-level|title=Nobody Has Beaten Doom's Hardest Difficulty Level|first=Jared|last=Petty|publisher=IGN|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref> The campaign also features 13 levels.<ref name=13-secret>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94931/doom-how-to-find-all-13-classic-maps|title=''Doom'': How to Find All 13 Classic Maps|first=Cassidee|last=Moser|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 30, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of the levels have multiple pathways and open areas, which allow players to explore and find collectibles and secrets throughout the levels. Many of these collectibles can be used as part of ''Doom''{{'}}s progression system, including weapon mods, rune powers, and Praetor Suit upgrades. Weapon points come from field drones and allow the player to unlock alternate modes of fire for many weapons, such as explosive shots and different rate and output of firepower. Each of the weapons' firing modes can be further upgraded using weapon tokens, but they can only be maxed out by completing a challenge related to that particular firing mode. Runes transport the player to a separate arena to perform a combat challenge that grants different abilities when successfully completed, such as better equipment drops from fallen enemies. Players can also upgrade their \"Praetor Suit\" by retrieving special tokens from dead marines and using them to improve functionality such as equipment, navigation and resistances.<ref name=pg-custom>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/11/11657360/doom-trailer-campaign-progression-system|title=''Doom'' developers explain the campaign's progression system|first=Samit|last=Sarkar|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref> Other pickups include small [[Doomguy]] figurines that allow the player to view 3D models of different characters, and data files that expand on the characters and story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/05/surprise-dooms-campaign-is-actually-fun/|title=Surprise, DOOM's Campaign Is Actually Fun|first=Alex|last=Walker|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, each of the game's levels contains a hidden lever which opens an area extracted from a classic level in the original ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' or ''[[Doom II]]''. Finding each of these areas unlocks them, making them accessible from the game's main menu in a section called ''Classic Maps''.<ref name=13-secret/>\n\n===Multiplayer===\nIn ''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer mode, several modes, such as team [[deathmatch]] and its variation \"Soul Harvest\", as well as Freeze Tag, Warpath ([[King of the Hill (game)|King of the Hill]] with a moving 'hill'), Domination, and \"Clan Arena\" (team [[Last man standing (video games)|last man standing]] with no pickups), exist within the game.<ref name=gem_e3>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/06/doom-unveiled-coming-spring-2016|title=Doom unveiled, coming spring 2016|first=Sal|last=Romano|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=June 5, 2016|website=Gematsu}}</ref> Players can also use power-ups and teleporters in a multiplayer match. They can pick up a Demon Rune, one of the power-ups featured, to transform into and fight as a demon. There are four demons available initially in the game, each of which has different abilities: the Revenant, the Baron of Hell, the Mancubus, and the Prowler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-03-25-doom-details-its-four-playable-demons|title=''Doom'' details its four playable demons|first=Jeffrey|last=Matulef|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 25, 2016|accessdate=June 21, 2016}}</ref> At launch, the game featured nine maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/new-doom-teaser-showcases-nine-multiplayer-maps/?|title=New Doom teaser showcases nine multiplayer maps|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPlayers are granted [[experience point]]s upon each match. After they have collected sufficient experience points, players can level up, by which new armor, skins, weapons, and power-ups would be unlocked for players to use. Both the player character and weapon can be customized extensively by applying new skins and colors onto them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-multiplayer-progression-armor/|title=Doom character customization mixes Call of Duty and a ton of armor|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In addition, players can receive hack modules while playing the game, which are special abilities that can only be used once after they are collected. There are over six types of modules. Scout reveals the locations of all enemies to the player for a limited time after respawning, while Vital Signs shows all enemies' health. Retribution allows players to track their last killer by revealing that player's health and location, while Power Seeker guides players to the power weapon pickup in the game. The Resupply Timer, meanwhile, shows the respawn time of the power-up items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/dooms-hack-modules-will-offer-temporary-multiplayer-boosts/|title=Doom's Hack Modules will offer temporary multiplayer boosts|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|date=February 22, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> Players can also perform taunts in the game's multiplayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-03-30-yes-you-can-do-the-carlton-dance-in-the-new-doom|title=Yes, you can do the Carlton dance in the new Doom|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 30, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, Update 6.66 was released for ''Doom''<nowiki/>'s multiplayer. Update 6.66 features a revised progression system, all three DLC bundled into the core game, a new 'rune' system (replacing the Hack Module system) and enhanced kill notifications. To accommodate this new progression system, Update 6.66 also reset all players' multiplayer experience progression, but not without giving players the option whether to retain all unlocked items or reset them. Players who played before Update 6.66 and players who obtained the 'Slayer' level received unique medals to show their status.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3lw31bjKOsagegSyIYWIEg/the-ultimate-doom-update-6-66-all-dlc-unlocked-free-weekends|title=The \u2018Ultimate\u2019 DOOM \u2013 Update 6.66, All DLC Unlocked, Free Weekends|last=Stratton|first=Marty|date=|work=|access-date=July 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Level creation tool===\nIn all of its platforms except the Nintendo Switch, ''Doom'' includes a built-in [[Level editor|level creation tool]] called \"SnapMap\" which allows players to create and edit maps with their own structure and game logic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/14/8779769/doom-snapmap-pc-ps4-xbox-one|title=Doom SnapMap lets users create and share their own gameplay modes|first=Samit|last=Sarker|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> With SnapMap, players can create maps for different modes, ranging from single-player levels to co-operative or competitive multiplayer maps. When players are building a level, the game will shift to a top-down view. Players can place rooms and hallways to form a level and connect them together. If they are not connected together, the color of the construction pieces changes to notify the player. Players can also use the X-ray camera which temporarily removes all the walls to allow players to view the objects inside. Players can also place enemies into their maps, with the exception of the campaign's [[boss (video games)|bosses]]. Their [[artificial intelligence]] and stats, and the player's own movement speed can also be modified. Players can also add additional particle effects, lighting effects, and other gameplay items, such as health packs and ammo pick-ups.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\"/> Only in-game assets can be used, and players cannot create or import their own models into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/05/20/doom-snapmap-review/|title=DOOM SnapMap: A Brilliant & Accessible Modding Tool With Infuriating Restrictions|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Levels can be tested before they are published online.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\"/>\n\nFor players who do not wish to create extensively, the game features an AI conductor which automatically generates enemies.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/29/doom-snapmap-hands-on.aspx|title=Hands On With Doom's SnapMap|first=Andrew|last=Reiner|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=January 29, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Players receive \"snap points\" after they create a level or play a level created by other users. These points can be used to unlock additional cosmetic items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-snapmap-toolset-showcased-in-lengthy-dev-video/|title=Doom SnapMap toolset showcased in lengthy dev video|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=April 26, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Players can share their completed maps with other players. They can vote on and even modify other players' content and share them while citing the originals' authors.<ref name=gi-snapmap-easy>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/27/infinite-doom-why-snapmap-is-id-s-secret-weapon.aspx|title=Infinite ''Doom'': Why SnapMap Is id's Secret Weapon|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''Doom'' takes place during the year 2162{{efn|Although the year is never specified in the game, its sequel, ''[[Doom Eternal]]'', is set in 2163, specifying a eight month gap from the events of the 2016 game.}} in a research facility on Mars owned by the Union Aerospace Corporation, run by Dr. Samuel Hayden, a UAC scientist whose mind now inhabits an android body after having lost his original to brain cancer. Researchers at the UAC facility have attempted to draw energy from Hell, an alternative dimension inhabited by demons, in order to solve an energy crisis on Earth using the Argent Tower, which siphons energy and allows travel to and from Hell.<ref name=vb-plot>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/05/27/the-deanbeat-doom-is-a-memorable-trip-back-into-shooting-hell/|title=''The DeanBeat'': ''Doom'' is a memorable trip back into shooting hell|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> To supplement their work, Hayden organizes several expeditions into Hell, bringing back captive demons and artifacts for study. Among them is a [[sarcophagus]] containing the [[Doomguy|Doom Slayer]] (along with his Praetor Suit), who the demons imprisoned after his earlier rampage through Hell.\n\nThe facility is overrun by demons after one of Hayden's researchers, Olivia Pierce, makes a pact with them and uses the Tower to open a portal to Hell.<ref name=vb-plot/> In desperation, Hayden releases the Doom Slayer from his sarcophagus to repel the demonic invasion and close the portal. The Doom Slayer recovers his Praetor Suit and fights his way through the overrun facility, where he realigns a comms satellite dish to get a lay of the land, all guided by the AI VEGA. After clearing out the facility core and preventing a meltdown, he pursues Pierce as she destroys the energy induction filters to Hayden's objections. He pursues Pierce up the tower, where she uses an Argent accumulator to open an explosive rift into Hell, destroying the Tower, and where the Slayer is sent back. \n\nFighting his way to a teleporter, the Doom Slayer returns to Mars and makes his way to a tram leading to Hayden. Hayden informs the Slayer of the Helix Stone, an artifact used to study and harness Hell's energy. Entering the Lazarus labs, he observes the Helix Stone, and he learns of the Well, where the portal is powered, and of the magical key-like blade, the Crucible. He makes another excursion into Hell after battling and defeating a contained Cyberdemon and activating its accumulator, and fights through a labyrinthine gauntlet to recover the Crucible from a trio of Hell Guards. Arriving at VEGA's facility in the frozen north, he destroys the AI (while also making a backup copy), using its power to enter the Well, where he uses the Crucible to destroy the portal's power source. Finally, he confronts Pierce, who is transformed by the demons into the monstrous Spider Mastermind, and kills her.\n\nUpon the Doom Slayer's return to Mars, Hayden confiscates the Crucible, which he plans to use in his research. Despite all that has happened, he insists that Earth is too desperate for energy to give up. To keep the Doom Slayer from interfering with his plans, Hayden teleports him to an undisclosed location, saying that they [[Doom Eternal|will meet again]].\n\n==Development==\n===As ''Doom 4''===\n[[File:A screenshot of the canned Doom 4.jpg|thumb|A screenshot of the canceled ''Doom 4'', which showcased a more urban environment than its predecessors]]\n\n[[John Carmack]], co-founder of and then lead developer at [[id Software]], indicated that ''Doom 4'' was in development at [[QuakeCon]] on August 3, 2007.<ref name=\"carmackrage\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200708/N07.0803.1731.12214.htm?Page=2|title=QuakeCon 2007: John Carmack Talks ''Rage'', Id Tech 5 And More|last=Berghammer|first=Billy|date=August 3, 2007|work=Game Informer|accessdate=August 24, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029050912/http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200708/N07.0803.1731.12214.htm?Page=2|archivedate=October 29, 2007}}</ref> It was announced in May 2008.<ref name=\"ign_announce\">{{cite web |last=Ocampo |first=Jason |date=May 7, 2008 |accessdate=May 7, 2008 |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/872/872097p1.html |title=''Doom 4'' Announced|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Id Software CEO [[Todd Hollenshead]] suggested that like ''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]'', the game would take place on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/DOOM-4-Rage-FPS-John-Carmack-id-Tech-5,14837.html|title=Are These Really ''Doom 4'' Screenshots?|first=Kevin|last=Parrish|work=[[Tom's Hardware]]|publisher=[[Purch Group]]|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> Carmack stated that it would feature gameplay more akin to the original ''Doom'' games rather than the [[survival horror]] gameplay of ''[[Doom 3]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/85484-John-Carmack-Sheds-Some-Light-On-Doom-4 |title=John Carmack Sheds Some Light On Doom 4 |first=Andy|last=Chalk|date=August 6, 2008|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Carmack claimed that Doom 4 would look \"three times better\" than ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]'' even though it was intended to run at 30 frames per second on Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, rather than the 60 that ''Rage'' was targeting.<ref name=1up-new>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/doom-game-announced|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714131428/http://www.1up.com/news/doom-game-announced|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 14, 2012|title=Next ''Doom'' Game Announced|first=Philip|last=Kollar|work=[[1UP.com|1UP]]|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=July 31, 2008|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> It was planned to run at 60 frames per second on Windows with state-of-the-art hardware.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.maximumpc.com/article/news/quakecon_08_quake_live_will_have_no_mod_support_doom_4_run_60hz_pc_locked_30hz_consoles | title=QuakeCon 08: Quake Live Will Have No Mod Support; Doom 4 to Run at 60Hz on PC, Locked at 30Hz for Consoles |date=July 31, 2008 |first=Norman|last=Chan|publisher=[[Maximum PC]]|accessdate=November 30, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628192231/http://www.maximumpc.com/article/news/quakecon_08_quake_live_will_have_no_mod_support_doom_4_run_60hz_pc_locked_30hz_consoles|archivedate=June 28, 2011}}</ref> Carmack also stated that the game was running on the [[id Tech 5]] game engine.<ref name=1up-new/> In 2009, he revealed that the multiplayer component was being developed separately and would run at 60 frames per second.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N_Ge-35Ld70 | title=John Carmack on Rage |date=July 2009 |work=[[YouTube]]|publisher=CD-Action |accessdate=October 30, 2010}}</ref> He stated in 2011 that \"you can't have 30 guys crawling all over you at 60 frames per second at this graphics technology level because it's painful.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6318725/e3-2011-john-carmack-talks-wii-u-playstation-vita-and-next-gen-rage |title=E3 2011: John Carmack talks Wii U, PlayStation Vita, and next-gen Rage|date=June 9, 2011|first=Tor|last=Thorsen|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=June 9, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128080308/http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6318725/e3-2011-john-carmack-talks-wii-u-playstation-vita-and-next-gen-rage|archivedate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, Hollenshead said that ''Doom 4'' was \"deep in development\". Asked whether ''Doom 4'' would be a sequel, a reboot, or a prequel, his response was \"It's not a sequel to ''Doom 3'', but it's not a reboot either. ''Doom 3'' was sort of a reboot. It's a little bit different than those.\"<ref name=\"GameSpotApr09Doom4\">{{cite web|last=Thorsen |first=Tor |date=April 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 10, 2009 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6207773.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=topstory&tag=topstory;title |title=Hollenshead Rages about PC gaming, E3 surprises|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104071832/http://www.gamespot.com/news/hollenshead-rages-about-pc-gaming-e3-surprises-6207773|archivedate=November 4, 2012}}</ref> On June 23, 2009, [[ZeniMax Media]], parent company of [[Bethesda Softworks]], acquired id Software and announced that future id games would be published by Bethesda Softworks, including ''Doom 4''.<ref name=\"doompublisher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6243433.html/ |title=Bethesda publishing Rage |last=Magrino |first= Tom |date=December 15, 2009 |work=GameSpot |accessdate=March 1, 2014 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091218064325/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6243433.html |archivedate = December 18, 2009}}</ref> Id Software creative director [[Tim Willits]] announced that key releases would be much sooner and that the partnership allowed id Software to have two teams, each having a project in parallel development, for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/08/16/doom-4-coming-sooner-than-you-think|title=''Doom 4'' Coming Sooner Than You Think|first=Jim|last=Reilly|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> Carmack added that, once ''Rage'' was complete, its development team would move to ''Doom 4''. ''Doom 4'' might also feature dedicated servers unlike ''Rage''.<ref name=\"Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4zgYG-_ha28|title=Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011 |date=August 5, 2011|author=QuakeCon Official|publisher=[[ZeniMax Media]]|work=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2011 QuakeCon, Carmack mentioned that the new ''Doom'' would be using a new scripting language based on [[C++]] and called it \"super-script\", a superset of C++ with features such as scheduling and [[type safety]].<ref name=\"Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011\" /> At the end of 2012, the team decided to make ''Doom 4'' a reboot.<ref name=metro-interview>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/07/02/doom-id-software-interview-they-just-love-blowing-up-barrels-5276385/|title=''Doom'' id Software interview \u2013 \u2018They just love blowing up barrels!\u2019|first=David|last=Jenkins|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In November 2013, Carmack left id Software to commit to his work at [[Oculus Rift|Oculus VR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/11/22/john-carmack-leaves-id-software-to-focus-on-oculus-vr/|title=John Carmack leaves id Software to focus on Oculus VR|first=Jon|last=Fingas|date=November 22, 2013|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]}}</ref>\n\n{{quotebox|quote=\"Every game has a soul. Every game has a spirit. When you played ''Rage'', you got the spirit. And [''Doom 4''] did not have the spirit, it did not have the soul, it didn't have a personality.\"|author=Tim Willits|source=[[QuakeCon]] 2013<ref name=ign-character/>|width=20%}}\n\nIn April 2013, [[Kotaku]] published an [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9]] describing ''Doom 4'' as trapped in \"[[development hell]]\". Citing connections to id, the article claimed that ''Doom 4'' had suffered under mismanagement and that development was completely restarted in 2011. Inside sources described the pre-2011 version\u2014which was to portray the uprising of Hell on Earth\u2014as heavily [[Scripted sequence|scripted]] and cinematic, comparing it to the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' franchise. The pre-2011 version was criticized as mediocre and the new version as \"lame\" and a \"mess\".<ref name=\"kotaku.com\">{{cite web|last=Schreier |first=Jason |url=http://kotaku.com/five-years-and-nothing-to-show-how-doom-4-got-off-trac-468097062 |title=Five Years And Nothing To Show: How Doom 4 Got Off Track |publisher=[[Kotaku]] |date=April 3, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> While Hollenshead initially stated that the ''Doom 4'' team was doing something that fans would be happy with,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-04-19-doom-fans-will-be-happy-with-doom-4|title=''Doom'' fans \"will be happy\" with ''Doom 4''|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> id's Willits criticized the game's lack of character in QuakeCon 2013.<ref name=ign-character>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/02/id-software-pushing-boundaries-focusing-only-on-doom-4|title=id Software 'Pushing Boundaries,' Focusing Only on Doom 4|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=August 2, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> In July 2015, Marty Stratton criticized ''Doom 4''{{'}}s lack of personality as id's primary reason to cancel the game, and pointed out its similarities to the ''Call of Duty'' franchise and that the game was not the product that id thought people wanted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/call-doom-died-because-it-didnt-match-game-we-think-you-wanted-play/|title=''Call of DOOM'' died because it \"didnt match the game we thought people wanted\"|first=Leon|last=Hurley|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 video documentary by [[Noclip]], ''Doom'' creative director Hugo Martin described the \"Hell on Earth\" premise as: \"It was like [[Robert Zemeckis]]. See [[Contact (1997 American film)|''Contact'']], like, if this really happened. Now let's be clear: it was awesome. But it was more realistic. It was about the global impact of a Hellish invasion.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=[[Noclip]]|title=DOOM Resurrected - To Hell & Back (DOOM Documentary)|date=December 12, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PS6SBnccxMA|accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The creative director of the ''Doom 4'' prototype, [[Kevin Cloud]], said in the same interview, \"As far as the upper-level creative direction, that was me driving that. And honestly, again, taking it in a direction I don't think the fans would have enjoyed.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===As ''Doom''===\nAfter the game's redesign began, Willits revealed in August 2013 that ''Doom'' was still the team's focus.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-4-still-exists-bethesda-unveils-doom-beta/1100-6417840/ |title=Doom 4 still exists: Bethesda unveils Doom beta|first=Martin|last=Gaston|work=[[GameSpot]] |date=February 19, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2015}}</ref> British science fiction writer [[Graham Joyce]] was enlisted to write the game's story; after Joyce died in 2014, Adam Gascoine was brought in as a replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/23/11745422/how-doom-lived-up-to-nearly-a-decades-worth-of-expectations|title=How ''Doom'' lived up to nearly a decade's worth of expectations (update)|first=Brian|last=Crecente|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> Sound designer Chad Mossholder was recruited to write flavor text, after the team found out he writes [[comic]]s.<ref>https://www.shacknews.com/article/99662/stairway-to-badass-the-making-and-remaking-of-doom?page=4</ref>\n\nA [[teaser trailer]] of ''Doom'' was presented at [[E3 2014]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/conferences/e32014/11630-Doom-Reboot-Revealed-by-Bethesda|title=''Doom'' Reboot Revealed by Bethesda|first=Steven|last=Bogos|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and on the QuakeCon and ''Doom'' websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doom.com/en-us/|title=''DOOM'' official website|publisher=[[id Software]]|accessdate=June 11, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611054229/http://doom.com/en-us/|archivedate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> A more expansive trailer was unveiled at QuakeCon 2014 on July 17, wherein a closed presentation was made mainly to silence ongoing rumors of the project being in jeopardy.<ref name=quakecon>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-was-revealed-to-counter-fears-of-trouble-at-id-software-public-reveal-unlikely-this-year/|title=Doom was revealed to counter fears of trouble at id Software, public reveal unlikely this year|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> Id Software executive producer Marty Stratton, the host of the presentation, announced that ''Doom 4'' had been renamed ''Doom'' as \"it\u2019s an origin game, reimagining everything about the originals\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2014/07/18/doom-4-details-quakecon-2014-reboot/|title=Why id Software is calling it \"Doom\" and not \"Doom 4\"|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref> In light of [[Crytek]]'s financial difficulties, it was announced that Tiago Sousa, head R&D graphics engineer at Crytek, was leaving to join the ''Doom'' and id Tech 6 engine team as a lead programmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/07/19/eleven-year-crytek-engineer-veteran-joins-id-software/|title=Eleven year Crytek engineer veteran joins id Software|first=Thomas|last=Schulenberg|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Games Industry International]]|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quotebox|align=left|quote=It all kind of gets tossed into a big pot of soup, and you're saying, \"Does it feel fun, or does it not feel fun?\", and then you make your decisions along those lines, but I think [the progression system]'ll be an important part of ''Doom'', and I think people will be excited about it when they get a sense of what we're doing.|author=Marty Stratton|source=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''<ref name=pg-multi/>|width=20%}}\nBethesda released a teaser trailer to promote gameplay being shown at [[E3 2015]] on June 14, 2015; the trailer depicted the double-barreled shotgun and the Revenant, a monster returning to the game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-18-a-very-brief-look-at-the-new-doom | title=A (very) brief look at the new Doom |first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]] | publisher=Gamer Network | date=May 18, 2015 | accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> On June 14, around 15 minutes of gameplay footage were shown at E3.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pitcher |first=Jenna |date=June 14, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/15/e3-2015-doom-release-date-announced |title=E3 2015: DOOM Release Date Announced |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Regarding the progression system, Marty Stratton thought that it was important to allow players personalization and customization.<ref name=pg-multi>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/23/9027433/doom-4-multiplayer-preview-gameplay-loadouts-unlocks|title=''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer mixes modern and retro, but it's still the fastest game in town|first=Griffin|last=McElroy|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nid felt the greatest challenge was to compete with other first-person shooters such as ''[[Call of Duty]]'' and ''[[Battlefield (video game series)|Battlefield]],'' as younger players were less familiar with the older ''Doom'' franchise. They also found it difficult to establish a game with its own identity while \"being faithful\" to other games in the series. The team consulted the game directors at [[Bethesda Game Studios]], who Stratton considered \"[had gone] through the same thing when they were working on ''[[Fallout 3]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-devs-talk-challenges-of-rebooting-the-series/1100-6429176/|title=Doom Devs Talk Challenges of Rebooting the Series|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Doom 2016 reversible cover.jpeg|thumb|250px|This cover is similar to and inspired by the original game's cover art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/03/07/hated-doom-39-s-cover-vote-for-your-reverse-sleeve-pick.aspx|title=[Update] A Winner Has Been Named In ''Doom'' Alternate Art Vote|first=Jeff|last=Cork|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> After being favored by fans, and in response to criticisms of the primary cover, this reversible cover was elected to be the official one. It was used later by the [[Nintendo Switch]] port as the default box art.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=DOOM|number=908386725860388864|date=September 13, 2017|title=From Mars, to Hell, to the palm of your hand. DOOM arrives on NintendoSwitch in Holiday 2017!}}</ref>]]\n\nOn July 2, 2015, Stratton revealed that the game would not take place on Earth and that, unlike ''Doom 3,'' the game was comic and \"very juvenile\".<ref name=metro-interview/> Director Hugo Martin later said that the game was heavily inspired by [[rock and roll]] and ''[[He-Man and the Masters of the Universe]]'' and that its Hell-themed levels would feature much [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]]. ''Doom''{{'}}s world was designed to have personality and be \"over the top\"; the UAC industrial field was designed to be the massive underbelly of the corporation, the UAC corporate field zone was designed to be much cleaner in terms of splattered goriness than the other zones to prevent repetition. Skulls were used in Hell as iconic elements and the Titan's Realm zone was constructed from dead, ancient, colossal demons.<ref name=gi-gruesome/> At QuakeCon 2015, it was announced that the game would run at 1080p and 60 frames per second on console, as id considered it \"the most necessary graphical goal\" which could effectively improve gameplay fluidity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-dev-we-want-to-be-the-best-looking-game-out-t/1100-6429178/|title=Doom Dev: \"We Want to Be the Best-Looking Game Out There at 60 FPS and 1080p\"|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 25, 2015|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref> According to Martin, the team put little emphasis on story, as they believed that it was not an important feature of the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-is-totally-rock-n-roll-dev-says/1100-6433576/|title=Doom Is Totally Rock 'N Roll, Dev Says|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Instead, they added codex items to let interested players speculate about the story and the identity of the player character.<ref name=\"Jason-O'Connell\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/07/02/how-doom-tells-players-part-of-the-story-and-leaves-them-guessing/|title=How ''Doom'' reveals its secrets like a ''Frank Frazetta'' painting|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=July 2, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Stratton and Martin, movement is the game's most important pillar. To help keep movement fast, weapon reloading was excluded and levels were designed to discourage players from hiding.<ref name=glory-kills>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/18/see-how-id-39-s-new-doom-breaks-the-modern-shooter-mold.aspx|title=See How id's New ''Doom'' Breaks The Modern Shooter Mold|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> On January 25, Stratton confirmed the game's feature of nonlinear exploration and stated that combat is the game's focus and that the difficulty of the game was raised with the aim of creating an ultimate first-person shooter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/637803/Doom-Update-PS4-Xbox-One-Difficulty-Level-Non-Linear-Exploration-Confirmed|title=''Doom'' update: Late changes made as non-linear exploration is confirmed|first=Anthony|last=Chapman|work=[[Daily Express]]|publisher=[[Express Newspapers]]|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, 2016, the release date of the ''Doom'' beta, a cinematic trailer directed by [[Joe Kosinski]] was created to evoke the game's three core pillars: incessant combat, terrifying demons, and powerful guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-doom-live-action-trailer-from-tron-legacy-di/1100-6436174/|title=Watch ''Doom'' Live-Action Trailer From Tron: Legacy Director|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Doom''{{'}}s [[multiplayer]] was developed in conjunction with [[Certain Affinity]].<ref name=ca-multi>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-new-doom-multiplayer-trailer-closed-beta-dat/1100-6435474/|title=Watch New ''Doom'' Multiplayer Trailer, Closed Beta Dates Announced For PS4, Xbox One, and PC|first=Zorine|last=Te|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=March 9, 2016|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> SnapMap was developed in conjunction with [[Escalation Studios]] and designed to be powerful,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escalation.com/project/doom|title=DOOM Escalation Studios|website=Escalation Studios|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> to give players the opportunity to create their own content as part of the ''Doom'' and id legacies, and target those who have no experience or expertise in traditional [[Mod (video games)|modding]].<ref name=gi-snapmap-easy/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/264518/Dooms_usergen_mode_SnapMap_Its_not_mods_but_heres_what_it_is.php|title=''Doom''{{'}}s user-gen mode, SnapMap: It's not mods, but here's what it ''is''|first=Christian|last=Nutt|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM plc|UBM]]|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\nThe ''Doom'' soundtrack was composed by [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]], with additional contributions by [[Richard Devine]]. Gordon aimed to treat the game's original soundtrack with \"utmost respect\" while modernizing it; however, the team at id stipulated in the initial brief that they wanted \"no guitars\" on the soundtrack, fearing that it would make the game \"feel like ''[[Bill & Ted]]''\"<ref name=\"noclipMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r0nOsuaPDeg|title=DOOM Documentary: Part 3 - Guns, Guitars & Chess on Mars|first=|last=[[Noclip]]|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and that [[heavy metal music]] itself has become \"a bit of a joke\".<ref name=\"GDCMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U4FNBMZsqrY|title=DOOM: Behind the Music|first=|last=GDC|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> Gordon's initial concept was based around the idea of Argent energy corrupting human-made devices; to mirror this in music, he fed basic waveforms \u2013 [[sine wave]]s and [[white noise]] \u2013 through a complex array of [[effects unit]]s such as distortion and compression.<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> While this resulted in a unique electronic sound, the game still wasn't \"sounding like ''Doom''\"; Gordon then gradually started adding more and more guitar elements, which eventually resulted in the desired tone and feel for the game; Gordon used [[seven-string guitar|seven-]] and [[eight-string guitar]]s to give the music a lower tone, and used a [[nine-string guitar]] for the game's main theme, a variation on [[Bobby Prince]]'s \"E1M1\" / \"At DOOM's Gate\" theme;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ua-f0ypVbPA|title=''DOOM'': Behind The Music Part 1|first=Mick|last=Gordon|work=[[YouTube]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=June 5, 2016}}</ref> Gordon would eventually admit that using a nine-string was \"kinda stupid\" in its excess, and that while he eventually sold the guitar to [[Fredrik Thordendal]] from [[Meshuggah]], \"even he can't find a use for it\".<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> The soundtrack contains numerous [[easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s: some songs reference themes or sounds from older ''Doom'' games, others contain [[backmasking]] (\"Jesus loves you\"), images of pentagrams and the number 666 embedded into the sound via [[steganography]]. Gordon intended these as a joke, and never thought anyone would find them,<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> but they were discovered shortly after release and widely covered in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/31/11825606/doom-2016-soundtrack-satan-666-inverted-pentagram|title=Satanic figures are hidden in Doom's soundtrack|first=Nick|last=Statt|date=May 31, 2016|website=The Verge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/doom-soundtrack-includes-satanic-messages-hidden-in-the-game-s-audio-a7057261.html|title=There are terrifying, satanic messages hidden in the Doom soundtrack|date=May 31, 2016|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/dooms-soundtrack-hides-a-satanic-easter-egg-1779657359|title=Doom's Soundtrack Hides A Satanic Easter Egg|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|website=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack was widely praised and won the Best Music / Sound Design award at [[The Game Awards 2016]]; Gordon, joined by [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]] drummer Matt Halpern and ''[[Quake II]]'' composer [[Sascha Dikiciyan]] (aka Sonic Mayhem), performed a short medley of the soundtracks \"Rip and Tear\" and \"BFG Division\" as well as ''Quake II''{{'}}s \"Descent Into Cerberon\" live at the awards show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/12/2/13815036/watch-the-doom-soundtrack-live-the-game-awards-2016|title=performed live at The Game Awards 2016|first=Ashley|last=Oh|date=December 2, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2012|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> The soundtrack was released in September 2016. It contains 31 tracks from the game, over 2 hours of music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/09/doom-reboots-killer-dynamic-soundtrack-has-finally-been-sequenced-as-an-lp/|title=Rip and tear your eardrums with Doom 2016\u2019s soundtrack, finally loosed from the game|first=Sam|last=Machkovech|work=[[Ars Technica]]|date=September 28, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release and marketing==\n\n\nOn February 19, 2014, Bethesda revealed that access to a beta version of ''Doom 4'', titled ''Doom'', would be available for those who pre-ordered ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'' on any of the supportable platforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bethblog.com/2014/02/19/get-psyched-wolfenstein-release-date-first-details-on-doom-beta/ |title=''Wolfenstein: The New Order'' Out 5/20, Pre-order for ''Doom'' Beta Access|first=Matt|last=Grandstaff|work=[[PlayStation Blog]]|publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]]|date=February 19, 2014|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> Those players were also eligible for selection to participate in the game's multiplayer-only limited alpha, which ran between December 3 and 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/bethesda-to-host-limited-doom-multiplayer-alpha-in-the-coming-months-3422123|title=Bethesda to host limited DOOM multiplayer alpha 'in the coming months'|first=Jordan|last=Biazzo|work=[[Gamereactor]]|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref> The beta began on March 31, 2016, and ended on April 3.<ref name=ca-multi/> It was followed by an open beta, which started on April 15, 2016, and ended on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/06/doom-open-beta-april-15th/|title='Doom' open beta kicks off April 15th|first=Jon|last=Fingas|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' was released for [[Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] on May 13, 2016, worldwide; an exception was Japan, where it was released on May 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/05/12/doom-heres-the-pc-requirements-and-launch-times-for-your-region/|title=''Doom'': here\u2019s the PC requirements and launch times for your region|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> It is also the first game of the ''Doom'' franchise to be released as uncensored in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/24/11105336/doom-uncut-german-release|title=''Doom'' launching uncut in Germany \u2014 a franchise first|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Bethesda partnered with [[Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsports]] for a special promotion that had [[Mikhail Aleshin]] driving a ''Doom''-styled car at the [[Indianapolis 500]] racing competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-branded-car-will-race-at-indy-500/1100-6439741/|title=Doom-Branded Car Will Race at Indy 500|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 23, 2016, ''Doom'' was made available for Xbox One owners to pre-order; for a limited time, they would also get the two original games, ''Doom'' and ''Doom II'', for free. Other bonuses included the Demon Multiplayer Pack, which offered a demon-themed armor set with three skin variations; six metallic paint colors and three id Software logo patterns used for character customization; and six sets of consumable Hack Module perks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/23/11098920/doom-pre-orders-backward-compatible-doom-free-xbox-one|title=''Doom'' pre-orders on Xbox come with original games for free|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 23, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/original-doom-doom-ii-xbox-one-doom-pre-order-bonus/|title=Get the original ''Doom'' and ''Doom II'' free by pre-ordering the Xbox One version of ''Doom''|first=Kristofer|last=Wouk|publisher=[[Digital Trends]]|date=February 23, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> There is also a Collector's Edition, which was significantly more expensive than the normal edition. It includes a figurine of the Revenant \u2013 a demon featured in the game \u2013 and a metal case.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-release-date-120-collectors-edition-announced/1100-6434481/|title=Doom Release Date, $120 Collector's Edition Announced|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 4, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nid Software replaced Certain Affinity to work on the multiplayer for Windows after the game's launch and promised to fix its issues and introduced new features such as private matches, custom game settings and an enhanced cheat detection system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/doom-s-multiplayer-is-being-taken-over-by-id-who-promises-to-fix-things-367266.phtml|title=Doom's multiplayer is being taken over by id, who promises to fix things|first=Brett|last=Makedonski|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref> At [[E3 2016]] on June 12, Bethesda Softworks announced its division, Bethesda VR, and that it was working on [[virtual reality]] support for the newly-released ''Doom'', set for release on an unspecified date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/06/13/doom-fallout-creator-dives-into-virtual-reality.html|title=''Doom'', ''Fallout'' creator dives into virtual reality|first=Chris|last=Morris|work=[[CNBC]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=June 13, 2016|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> Also at E3 2016 on that day, Bethesda Softworks and id Software announced the game's free demo, which was initially going to last for only a week but was extended indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-extends-free-doom-demo/|title=Bethesda extends free Doom demo|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=June 21, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> They also announced new multiplayer [[downloadable content]] titled ''Unto the Evil'', whose features include three maps and a new demon called the \"Harvester\", gun, equipment item, taunts, and armor sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2016/06/doom-unto-evil-multiplayer-dlc-announced|title=''Doom Unto the Evil'' multiplayer DLC announced|first=Sal|last=Romano|publisher=Gematsu|date=June 12, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> The DLC was released on August 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-08-04-dooms-unto-the-evil-dlc-is-now-available|title=Surprise! Doom's Unto the Evil DLC is now available|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=August 4, 2016|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Patch (computing)|Patch]]es for ''Doom'' were released after the game's release; these patches introduced a new photo mode, classic weapon pose,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-01-watch-the-new-dooms-classic-screen-centred-weapon-pose-in-action|title=Watch the new Doom's classic screen-centred weapon pose in action|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> and support for the [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]] API.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ryan|title=Doom Vulkan Patch Released|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/10483/doom-vulkan-patch-released|accessdate=July 13, 2016|publisher=[[AnandTech]]|date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> The Vulkan patch was expected to enable playable frame rates on older hardware. Subsequent benchmarks show up to a 66% improvement in the frame rates on [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] graphics cards, with minor changes in the performance of [[Nvidia]] cards.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kampman|first1=Jeff|title=Report: Doom's Vulkan renderer proves a boon for Radeons|url=https://techreport.com/news/30385/report-doom-vulkan-renderer-proves-a-boon-for-radeons|accessdate=July 13, 2016|publisher=[[The Tech Report]]|date=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, an update was released which unlocked the game's premium multiplayer DLCs to all owners, while also revamping the progression system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3lw31bjKOsagegSyIYWIEg/the-ultimate-doom-update-6-66-all-dlc-unlocked-free-weekends|title=The 'Ultimate' DOOM \u2013 Update 6.66, All DLC Unlocked, Free Weekends|first=Marty|last=Stratton|website=Bethesda.net}}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2017, it was announced via Nintendo Direct that ''Doom'' would release on Nintendo Switch during the fourth quarter of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grant|first1=Christopher|title=Wolfenstein 2: The New Colossus and Doom coming to Nintendo Switch|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/13/16305008/wolfenstein-2-doom-nintendo-switch-release-date|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref> The retail Switch version differs from the other console versions in that the multiplayer component is not included in the base product, but is instead offered as a free download, whereas the SnapMap component is not included at all, both changes as a result of cartridge limitations.<ref name=\"Switchsnapmap\">{{cite web|last1=Matulef|first1=Jeffery|title=Doom on Switch won't have SnapMap level editor|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-15-doom-on-switch-wont-have-snapmap-level-editor|website=Eurogamer|date=|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref> It was released on November 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dayus|first1=Oscar|title=Doom's Nintendo Switch Release Date Revealed|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/dooms-nintendo-switch-release-date-revealed/1100-6454094/|website=GameSpot|date=October 16, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> An update to the Switch version in February 2018 introduced the option to use the [[Motion controller|motion controls]] of the [[Joy-Con]]s for aiming, similar to other Switch games such as ''[[Splatoon 2]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kuchera|first1=Ben|title=Doom gets motion controls on the Nintendo Switch|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/2/20/17031590/doom-nintendo-switch-motion-controls|website=Polygon|date=February 20, 2018|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMonths after ''Doom'' was released, [[Zen Studios]] developed a [[Pinball#Computer pinball simulation|virtual]] [[pinball]] adaptation of the game as part of the ''Bethesda Pinball'' collection, which became available as part of ''[[Zen Pinball 2]]'', ''[[Pinball FX 2]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coppock |first1=Mark |title=Now you can play pinball versions of Doom, Fallout, and Elder Scrolls |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/bethesda-pinball-released-for-pinball-fx2/ |website=DigitalTrends |accessdate=November 24, 2018 |date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Pinball FX 3]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/pinball-fx-3-is-all-about-cross-platform-competition-1797931064 | title = Pinball FX 3 Is All About Cross-Platform Competition | first = Mike | last = Fahey | date = August 17, 2017 | accessdate = August 17, 2017 | work = [[Kotaku]]}}</ref>  as well as a separate [[free-to-play]] app for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web |last1=BarbieBobomb |title=Bethesda and Zen Studios Team Up for an Epic Pinball Pack |url=https://blog.zenstudios.com/?p=6672 |website=[[Zen Studios]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 |date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> At [[E3 2017]] Bethesda announced ''Doom VFR'', a [[virtual reality]] adaptation of ''Doom'', compatible with the [[PlayStation VR]] and [[HTC Vive]] headsets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-vfr-is-the-series-virtual-reality-debut/|title=Doom VFR is the series' virtual reality debut|date=June 11, 2017}}</ref> In ''Doom VFR'' the player assumes the role of Mars' last survivor who, after being killed, gets his consciousness uploaded into an artificial network, and is tasked with defeating the demons and restoring the facility's operations, having an array of electronic devices and weapons at his disposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/4KKxfa0osU6qSGQQwWqukY/from-mars-to-hell-in-doom-vfr|title=From Mars to Hell in DOOM VFR|website=Bethesda.net}}</ref> The game was released on December 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wccftech.com/skyrim-vr-doom-vfr-fallout-4-vr-release-dates-confirmed/|title=Skyrim VR, DOOM VFR And Fallout 4 VR Release Dates Confirmed|publisher=WCCFTech|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Pre-release===\nInitial reception of the QuakeCon 2014 trailer accumulated considerable acclaim among fans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2014/07/big-time-doom-fans-react-to-yesterdays-doom-reveal/|title=Big-Time ''Doom'' Fans React To Yesterday's ''Doom'' Reveal|first=Stephen|last=Totilo|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> and initial reception of the E3 2015 trailer was also positive, despite receiving criticisms by some critics, who considered the game to be too violent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/doom-launched-by-bethesda-at-e3-2015-swiftly-criticised-for-being-too-violent-10319985.html|title=Doom launched by Bethesda at E3 2015, swiftly criticised for being too violent|first=Andrew|last=Griffin|work=[[The Independent]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> Pete Hines from Bethesda Softworks responded by saying that the game is designed to allow players to apply violence on demons instead of humans. Hines added that, \"if you're not into [[graphic violence|violent, bloody]] games... ''Doom''{{'s}} probably not a game for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/23/8833293/bethesda-had-the-perfect-answer-for-people-bothered-by-dooms-violence|title=Bethesda had the perfect answer for people bothered by Doom's violence: \u00af\\_(\u30c4)_/\u00af|first=Ben|last=Kuchera|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the open multiplayer beta, [[IGN]] writer Nathan Lawrence called the beta disappointing, considering it less of a classic style \"arena shooter\" and unfavorable compared to other shooters such as ''[[Halo (franchise)|Halo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/04/13/why-dooms-multiplayer-really-isnt-an-arena-shooter|title=Why Doom's Multiplayer Really Isn't An Arena Shooter|first=Nathan|last=Lawrence|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref> Similarly, the beta was negatively received by players on [[Steam (service)|Steam]], with mostly negative reviews at the time when the beta was active.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/04/doom-is-now-bethesdas-second-most-hated-game-on-steam/|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|title=DOOM Is Now Bethesda's Second Most Hated Game On Steam|date=April 18, 2016|first=Alex|last=Walker}}</ref> Rock, Paper, Shotgun writer Adam Smith found the beta both to be similar to games such as ''[[Quake 3]]'', ''[[Unreal Tournament]]'', and the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series and not to feel like ''Doom'' itself, and criticized the weapon loadout concept.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/04/15/doom-beta-review/|title=Impressions: Knee Deep In ''DOOM''{{'}}s Open Beta|first=Adam|last=Smith|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> Review copies of the game were held back until release day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/where-is-our-review-for-doom--360163.phtml|title=Where is our review for Doom?|last=Furniss|first=Zack|work=Destructoid|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-release===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = wikidata\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref name=\"destructoidreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-doom-361942.phtml|title=Doom Review \u2013 Rip and Tear|last=Furniss|first=Zack|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| EGM = 8.5/10<ref name=\"egmreview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Buchholtz|first=Matt|publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2016}}</ref>\n| GI = 8.75/10<ref name=\"gameinformerreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/doom/b/playstation4/archive/2016/05/17/doom-review.aspx|title=Doom Review \u2013 A Bloody Welcome Rebirth|last=Bertz|first=Matt|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"gamerevreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/doom-2016|title=Doom (2016) Review: A nostalgia filled gore-fest of a masterpiece!|last=Henriquez|first=Mike|work=[[Game Revolution]]|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gamespotreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-6416432/|title=Doom Review: Our hero who art in hell, cursed be thy name.|last=Brown|first=Peter|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"gamesradarreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Houghton|first=David|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=May 19, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| GB = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"giantbombreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-745/|title=Doom Review|last=Shoemaker|first=Brad|work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=May 21, 2016|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.1/10<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/16/doom-review-2?page=2?page=2 |title=Doom Review|last=Gilory|first=Joab|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 88/100<ref name=\"pcgamerreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-review/|title=DOOM review|last=Davenport|first=James|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"polygonreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/18/11706108/doom-review-PC-xbox-one-PS4|title=DOOM review|last=Gies|first=Arthur|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"videogamer.comreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/doom_4_review.html|title=DOOM review (PS4)|last=Miller|first=Simon|work=VideoGamer.com|publisher=Candy Banana|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1=''[[Daily Express]]''\n|rev1Score={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=dereview/>\n|rev2=''[[Digital Spy]]''\n|rev2Score={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"DigitalSpyreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/review/a794296/doom-review-brtual-badass-and-so-close-to-the-doom-weve-always-wanted/|title=DOOM review: Brutal, badass and so close to the Doom reboot we always wanted|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n|rev3=''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n|rev3Score={{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=ttreview/>\n}}\n\n''Doom'' was released to positive reception regarding the fast-paced gameplay, single-player campaign, visuals and soundtrack whereas criticism was predominantly toward the multiplayer mode. Many critics believed that ''Doom'' was a successful return to form for the series. Following the wide release, the game received scores of 85/100 for PC and PlayStation 4 and 87/100 for the Xbox One on [[Metacritic]]. The Nintendo Switch edition, released in November 2017, was also positively received by professional reviewers, garnering a 79/100 on Metacritic: most reviewers praised the job of the port, also conceding that it's not as well-optimized as it was for previous consoles. The final version of the game received very positive reviews from users on [[Steam (service)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-05-18-the-new-doom-turns-around-steam-user-reviews|title=The new Doom campaign turns around Steam user reviews|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> It also received praise from other video game creators, including [[Cliff Bleszinski]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gears-of-war-designer-cliff-bleszinski-praises-new/1100-6439815/|title=Gears of War Designer Cliff Bleszinski Praises New Doom, But Has One Criticism|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref> and [[Greg Kasavin]], who said that the game answers questions that other modern shooters do not answer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/why-is-the-new-doom-so-important-it-asks-the-questions-other-shooters-aren-t-argues-supergiant-dev/0220857|title=Why is the new Doom so important? It asks the questions other shooters aren't, argues Supergiant dev|first=Matthew|last=Jarvis|work=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|date=May 26, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe game's single-player elements received critical acclaim. Alec Meer of Rock, Paper, Shotgun favorably compared ''Doom'' to the 2014 game ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'', also published by Bethesda, but added that ''Doom''{{'}}s quality surpassed that of ''Wolfenstein'' due to its fast pace and solid gunplay.<ref name=\"rockpapershotgun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/05/16/doom-review-pc/|title=Wot I Think: DOOM (Singleplayer)|last=Meer|first=Alec|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> Peter Brown of [[GameSpot]] praised single-player because he thought that the reboot captured the spirits of the older games, while refining them with modern elements. Brown also drew attention toward the soundtrack, calling it \"impactful\".<ref name=\"gamespotreview\"/> Gary Jones in the ''[[Daily Express]]'' felt that the game had one of the best single-player campaigns made for the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, successfully combining the traditional gameplay of the series with a very fast pace.<ref name=dereview>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/672439/DOOM-Review-Xbox-One-Bethesda-PS4|title=''DOOM'' Review: The best single-player FPS action on Xbox One and PS4|last=Jones|first=Gary|work=[[Daily Express]]|publisher=[[Express Newspapers]]|date=May 21, 2016|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Mike Henriquez of [[Game Revolution]] favored the visual and artistic design, calling it \"top-notch\".<ref name=\"gamerevreview\"/> Sam White in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' commended id Software for ''Doom''{{'}}s delivery of performance on all platforms and praised the weapon design for ''Doom''{{'}}s continuity to introduce new weapons at a perfect speed so that gamers always play with something new and exciting.<ref name=ttreview>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/what-to-play/doom-review/|title=''Doom'' is a fiendishly moreish, impeccably refined shooter - review|first=Sam|last=White|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]{{'}}s Arthur Gies remarked positively upon the exploration for collectables and secrets, and their relevance to the new upgrade feature, but he was critical of instances where the game would lock away sections of a level without warning.<ref name=\"polygonreview\"/> Zack Furniss of [[Destructoid]] was originally skeptical regarding the \"glory kills\" feature, as were other critics, fearing that they might distract from the fast-paced gameplay. He ultimately considered them to fit well in the flow of gameplay that keeps players in the middle of combat without a slowed pace.<ref name=\"destructoidreview\"/> [[Giant Bomb]]{{'}}s Brad Shoemaker felt that the glory kills' generating small amounts of health and armor \"makes them an essential part of the give-and-take of ''Doom''{{'}}s super fast combat; do you dart into the fray for a glory kill to get a little health back, and risk getting mobbed by all the other enemies around?\"<ref name=\"giantbombreview\"/> Conversely, Kyle Orland of [[Ars Technica]] felt that the glory kills' briefly taking control away from the player can easily disorient players or misposition them, finding them hard to ignore for players that choose not to use them.<ref name=\"arstechreview\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/05/doom-2016-single-player-review-back-to-basics/|title=Doom (2016) single-player review: Back to basics|last=Orland|first=Kyle|publisher=[[Ars Technica]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe SnapMap mode was also positively received with ''Hardcore Gamer''{{'s}} Jordan Helm's noting the possibilities yet simplicity with its use, calling it an \"admirable feat\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2016/05/17/review-doom/207490/|title=Doom Review (PS4)|last=Helm|first=Jordan|work=Hardcore Gamer|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Matt Peckham of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' thought that the mode added further value to the overall package of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4336416/doom-review/|title=Review: The New \u2018Doom\u2019 Serves Up a Brew of Nostalgia and Carnage|last=Peckham|first=Matt|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Matt Bertz of ''[[Game Informer]]'' commented upon the accessibility but criticized the lack of diverse settings and possible limitations when compared to a traditional community-based [[mod (video games)|mod]].<ref name=\"gameinformerreview\"/> James Davenport of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' compared it to the modification in the original games, which he views as one of the primary reasons why ''Doom'' is still a recognizable title. He was disappointed by the lack of mod support, though he nevertheless noted SnapMap for its simple use and variety of ideas already created by players.<ref name=\"pcgamerreview\"/>\n\nThe multiplayer mode, however, garnered a mixed reception from critics. IGN's Joab Gilory was less favorable toward the multiplayer, calling the overall game \"a tale of two very different shooters\", stating that multiplayer did not live up to the standard set by the single-player components and would not satisfy players.<ref name=\"IGN review\"/> Simon Miller of ''VideoGamer.com'' found the multiplayer to be only all right.<ref name=\"videogamer.comreview\"/> Matt Buchholtz of ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' criticized what he felt was the network's poor handling of latency, and failing to register on-target shots as hits in some instances while not in others.<ref name=\"egmreview\"/> Edwin Evans-Thirlwell of [[Eurogamer]] singled out the \"Warpath\" multiplayer mode as the most interesting of the match type, describing it as \"memorable\", while he regarded the other multiplayer modes as underdeveloped and underwhelming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-05-17-doom-review|title=Review: Doom's superb campaign makes up for underwhelming multiplayer in id Software's remarkable comeback.|last=Evans-Thirlwell |first=Edwin|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Julian Benson from [[Kotaku]] wrote that ''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer was very similar to other modern games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/doom-the-kotaku-review-1777315801|title=Doom: The Kotaku Review|last=Benson|first=Julian|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> More positively, however, David Houghton of [[GamesRadar]] enjoyed the multiplayer for the fast pace yet quick decision-making needed to succeed, calling it \"endlessly playable, smart, brutal fun.\"<ref name=\"gamesradarreview\"/> ''Doom'' was placed 1st in the GamesRadar's list of top FPS games of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 best FPS games of all time |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-fps-games/ |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=February 18, 2017 |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\nIt was the second best-selling retail game in its week of release in the UK, behind ''[[Uncharted 4: A Thief's End]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-05-16-uncharted-beats-doom-to-uk-retail-number-one|title=Uncharted beats Doom to UK retail number one|first=Dan|last=Pearson|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> This was reported to be 67% more in its first week than the previous entry, ''Doom 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-uncharted-4-has-strongest-debut-in/1100-6439822/|title=Top 10 UK Sales: Uncharted 4 Has Strongest Debut in Series History|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' was the second best-selling retail video game in the US in May 2016, also behind ''Uncharted 4''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/06/09/uncharted-4-leads-strong-month-of-software-sales-in-may-npd.aspx?|title=Uncharted 4 Leads Strong Month Of Software Sales In May NPD|first=Matt|last=Miller|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> By the end of May 2016, ''Doom''{{'}}s sales on the PC reached 500,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94944/doom-sales-reach-over-500k-on-pc-alone|title=''Doom'' sales reach over 500k on PC alone|first=Daniel|last=Perez|publisher=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 31, 2016|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The following month, by late June 2016, the game rose to number one in the UK charts, overtaking ''Uncharted 4'' and the later-released ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/431673/Charts+Doom+shoots+down+Overwatch/|title=Charts: Doom shoots down Overwatch|first=Chris|last=Martin|work=Game Reactor|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> and remained number one for a second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-chart-doom-remains-no1/1100-6441268/|title=Top 10 UK Sales Chart: Doom Remains No.1|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> The game had surpassed one million sold copies for PCs in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=DOOM Sells 1 Million Copies on Steam|url=http://techdrake.com/2016/08/doom-sells-1-million-copies-steam/|publisher=Techdrake|date=August 11, 2016}}</ref> By July 2017, the game reached two million copies sold on PC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wholesgame.com/news/doom-sells-2-million-copies-on-pc/|title=Doom sells 2 million copies on PC|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dualshockers.com/doom-surpasses-2-million-copies-sold-steam/|title=DOOM Surpasses 2 Million Copies Sold on Steam|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref> In November 2017 ''Doom'' was the fourth best-selling Switch game, during its debut week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/11/sonic_forces_on_switch_has_solid_uk_launch_as_doom_moves_up_the_charts|title=Sonic Forces on Switch Has Solid UK Launch as DOOM Moves Up the Charts|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=March 5, 2018|website=[[Nintendo Life]]}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Doom'' was featured in multiple lists by critics and media outlets as one of the best games of 2016, being featured in game of the year lists and articles including [[Giant Bomb]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/articles/giant-bombs-2016-game-of-the-year-awards-day-five/1100-5525/|title = Giant Bomb's 2016 Game of the Year Awards: Day Five |first=| last=| date=December 30, 2016| accessdate=January 1, 2016| work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> GameSpot,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/game-of-the-year-2016-countdown-10-6/1100-6446349/|title=GameSpot's Game of the Year 2016 Countdown: 10 - 6|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=December 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> GamesRadar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-games-2016/3/|title=GamesRadar+'s Game of the Year 2016|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=December 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[The Escapist (website)|The Escapist]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/17359-The-Escapist-Game-of-the-Year-2016#&gid=gallery_6734&pid=1|title=The Escapist's 2016 Game of the Year|work=[[The Escapist (website)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|date=January 1, 2017|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[The A.V. Club]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/our-favorite-games-2016-part-1-247166|title=Our favorite games of 2016, part 1 |work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=December 21, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> ''Rock, Paper, Shotgun'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/12/13/best-fps-2016-doom/|title=RPS 2016 Advent Calendar, Dec 13th: DOOM|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[Jim Sterling]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejimquisition.com/the-jimquisition-game-of-the-year-awards-2016/|title=The Jimquisition Game Of The Year Awards 2016|work=Jimquisition|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[VG247]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/12/26/vg247-games-of-the-year-awards-part-1-the-obvious-picks-were-not-even-sorry-for/|title=VG247 Games of the Year Awards, part 1: The Obvious Picks We\u2019re Not Even Sorry For|work=[[VG247]]|date=December 26, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[Daily Mirror]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/games-year-2016-best-video-9442676|title=Games of the Year 2016: The best video games this year, from Pok\u00e9mon GO to DOOM|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=December 31, 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[Zero Punctuation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/zero-punctuation/116977-Best-and-Worst-Games-of-2016|title=Best and Worst Games of 2016 &#124; Zero Punctuation Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist|website=www.escapistmagazine.com}}</ref> and [[Shacknews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/98296/game-of-the-year-2016-1-doom|title=Game of the Year 2016 #1: Doom|work=[[Shacknews]]|publisher=GamerHub|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Game Critics Awards]] 2015\n| Best Action Game\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/articles/best-of-e3-2015-game-critics-awards-announced/1100-5234/|title='Best of E3 2015' Game Critics Awards Announced|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best PC Game\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2016\n|rowspan=\"4\" | [[Golden Joystick Award]] 2016\n| Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/ |title = Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public |first=Sam| last=Loveridge| date=September 15, 2016| accessdate=November 18, 2016| work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Visual Design\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| PC Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[The Game Awards 2016]]\n| Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/all-the-2016-game-awards-nominees/1100-6445481/|title=All the 2016 Game Awards Nominees|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=November 18, 2016|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/12/1/13784410/the-game-awards-winners|title = The Game Awards: Here\u2019s the full winners list |first=Chelsea| last=Stark| date=December 1, 2016| accessdate=December 1, 2016| work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Game Direction\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Music/Sound Design\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Action Game\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences|Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences D.I.C.E. Awards]] 2016\n| Outstanding Achievement in Original Music Composition\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref name=\"dice2017\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/overwatch-wins-dice-game-of-the-year-full-nominees/1100-6448157/ |title= Overwatch Wins DICE Game of the Year, Full Nominees List |first1= Eddie  |last1= Makuch | first2= Jason | last2= Imms | date= February 23, 2017 | accessdate= May 8, 2017 |work= [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| Action Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Game Developers Choice Awards]] 2016\n| Best Audio\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"|<ref name=\"igf winners\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-the-game-developers-choice-awards-right-here/1100-6448326/ |title=Watch The Game Developers Choice Awards Right Here Tonight |first1= Eddie |last1= Makuch |first2= Jason |last2= Imms |date= March 1, 2017 |accessdate= May 8, 2017 |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Design\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Technology\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2017 [[SXSW Gaming Awards]]\n| Video Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\"|<ref name=\"2017 sxsw\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/articles/uncharted-4-wins-game-of-the-year-at-sxsw-awards/1100-6448819/ | title = Uncharted 4 Wins Game Of The Year At SXSW Awards | first = Eddie | last = Makuch | date = March 19, 2017 | accessdate = May 8, 2017 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| Excellence in Gameplay\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Animation\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Visual Achievement\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Musical Score\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | [[13th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| Audio Achievement\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web |date=April 6, 2017 |url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/games-awards-winners-list-2017 |title=Winners List for the British Academy Games Awards in 2017 |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Music\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" | [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]\n| Art Direction, Contemporary\n| {{won}}\n|rowspan=\"6\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=NAVGTR Awards (2016)|url=http://navgtr.org/winners/2016-awards/|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers}}</ref>\n|-\n| Control Design, 3D\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Control Precision\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Game Design, Franchise\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Game, Classic Revival\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Game, Franchise Action\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== Sequel ==\n{{Main|Doom Eternal}}\n\nAt the [[E3 2018]] press conference in June, Bethesda Softworks announced a sequel titled ''[[Doom Eternal]]''; gameplay footage was showcased at [[Quakecon]] 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/doom-is-getting-a-sequel-doom-eternal-1826717319 |title=Doom Is Getting A Sequel, Doom Eternal |date=June 10, 2018 |website=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref> It is based on [[id Tech 7]] and it was released on March 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttps://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/bethesda-apparently-broke-its-own-denuvo-protection-for-doom-eternal/|title=Bethesda apparently broke its own Denuvo protection for Doom Eternal|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://bethesda.net/en/game/doom-2016}}\n{{Portal bar|Solar System|Speculative fiction|Video games}}\n{{Doom series}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n[[Category:Bethesda Softworks games]]\n[[Category:Video games about demons]]\n[[Category:Doom (series)]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Id Software games]]\n[[Category:Id Tech games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Permadeath games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Stadia games]]\n[[Category:Video game reboots]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 22nd century]]\n[[Category:Video games set on Mars]]\n[[Category:Video games that support Vulkan]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One X enhanced games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Doom\n| image = Doom Cover.jpg\n| developer = [[id Software]]{{efn|Additional work for Nintendo Switch by [[Panic Button (company)|Panic Button]].}}\n| publisher = [[Bethesda Softworks]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|[[Marty Stratton]]|Hugo Martin}}\n| producer = Timothy Bell\n| programmer = Billy Ethan Khan\n| writer = Adam Gascoine\n| composer = [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]]\n| series = ''[[Doom (franchise)|Doom]]''\n| engine = [[id Tech 6]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]|[[Google Stadia|Stadia]]}}\n| released = {{Unbulleted list|'''Windows''', '''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''|May 13, 2016|'''Nintendo Switch'''|November 10, 2017}}\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Doom''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] video game developed by [[id Software]] and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]]. It was released worldwide on [[Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] in May 2016 and is powered by [[id Tech 6]]. A port for [[Nintendo Switch]] was co-developed with [[Panic Button (company)|Panic Button]] and released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stevivor.com/news/doom-on-switch-runs-at-30-fps-has-9gb-multiplayer-download/|title=DOOM on Switch runs at 30 FPS, has 9GB multiplayer download|publisher=Stevivor}}</ref> A reboot of the [[Doom (franchise)|''Doom'' franchise]], it is the fourth title in the main series and the first major installment since ''[[Doom 3]]'' in 2004.\n\n''Doom'' was announced as \"''Doom 4''\" in 2008, and that version underwent an extensive development cycle with different builds and designs before the game was restarted in 2011 and revealed as simply \"''Doom''\" in 2014. It was tested by customers who pre-ordered the 2014 Bethesda game ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'' and also by the general public. [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]] composed the music for the game, with additional music contributed by Ben F. Carney, Chris Hite, and Chad Mossholder.\n\nPlayers take the role of an [[Doomguy|unnamed space marine]] as he battles demonic forces from [[Hell]] that have been unleashed by the Union Aerospace Corporation on a future-set colonized planet [[Mars]]. The gameplay returns to a faster pace with more open-ended levels, closer to the first two games than the slower [[survival horror]] approach of ''Doom 3''. It also features environment traversal, character upgrades, and the ability to perform executions known as \"glory kills\". The game also supports an online multiplayer component and a level editor known as \"SnapMap\", co-developed with [[Certain Affinity]]{{efn|[[BattleCry Studios]] has since taken over Certain Affinity's development duties.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Mike|title=BattleCry devs now working with id on Doom multiplayer|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/443533/BattleCry+devs+now+working+with+id+on+Doom+multiplayer/|website=www.gamereactor.eu|publisher=[[Gamereactor]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>}} and [[Escalation Studios]], respectively.\n\n''Doom'' was well-received by critics and players. The single-player campaign, graphics, soundtrack, and gameplay received considerable praise, with reviewers crediting the game for recapturing the spirit of the classic ''Doom'' games and first-person shooters of the 1990s, whereas the multiplayer mode drew the most significant criticism. It was the second best-selling video game in North America and the UK a few weeks after its release and sold over 500,000 copies for PCs within the same time period. A sequel titled ''[[Doom Eternal]]'' was announced at [[E3 2018]] for Nintendo Switch, Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One and [[Google Stadia|Stadia]] and was released on March 20, 2020, with the Nintendo Switch port coming later in 2020.\n\n==Gameplay==\n\n===Single-player===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Output OK1Cm5.gif|thumb|left|250px|An animation of the [[Doom Slayer]] sawing two Imps, and the player gaining ammunition]] -->\n\nAccording to the game's executive producer [[Marty Stratton]], the key principles of ''Doom''{{'}}s single-player mode are \"badass demons, big effing guns, and moving really fast\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/hands-on-dooms-coolest-new-gun-is-powered-by-sprinting/|title=Hands-on: ''Doom''{{'}}s coolest new gun is powered by sprinting|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2016|first=Ian|last=Birnbaum|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> The game allows players to perform movements such as double jumps and ledge climbs throughout levels of industrial and corporate fields of a Union Aerospace Corporation (UAC) research facility on [[Mars]] and then levels of Hell,<ref name=gi-gruesome>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/11/video-the-gruesome-art-design-of-doom.aspx|title=The Gruesome Level Design Of ''Doom''|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 11, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> as the combat system puts emphasis upon momentum and speed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-revealed-at-quakecon-2014-and-heres-what-we-saw/|title=Doom revealed at QuakeCon 2014, and here's what we saw|first=Ian|last= Birnbaum |date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> The approach is known as \"push-forward combat\", which discourages players from taking cover behind obstacles or [[Health (games)#Regenerating health|resting to regain health]] while playing from the [[Doom Slayer]] 's perspective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/08/06/doom-cant-afford-to-let-you-hang-back/|title=''DOOM'' can\u2019t afford to let you hang back|first=Sherif|last=Saed|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> Players instead collect health and armor pick-ups by killing enemies. \"Glory Kills\" is a newly-introduced melee execution system; when enough damage has been dealt to an enemy, the game will highlight it and allow the player to perform a quick and violent melee takedown, rewarding the player with small health recovery.<ref name=glory-kills/>\n\nThe fights also require the player to develop simple tactics. As the game gets harder, the player needs to use the advantages of fight arenas and their bonuses smarter. They also need to decide which enemy has to be killed firstly and how to move on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Davenport|first=James|date=May 18, 2016|website=PC Gamer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/5/18/11706108/doom-review-PC-xbox-one-PS4|title=Doom Review|last=Gies|first=Arthur|date=May 18, 2016|website=Polygon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-6416432/|title=Doom Review|last=Brown|first=Peter|date=May 17, 2016|website=Gamespot|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe game features a large arsenal of weapons which can be collected and freely switched by players throughout the game and require no reloading. Recurring weapons of the series also make a return, including the super shotgun and [[BFG (weapon)|BFG 9000]]. The BFG has a very small ammunition capacity, but is extremely powerful. Similarly, the chainsaw returns, but has been reintroduced as a special-use weapon<ref name=gr-doom-development/> that relies upon fuel, but can be used to instantly cut through enemies and provide a greater-than-normal drop of ammunition for the player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/20/the-explosive-modified-arsenal-of-doom.aspx|title=The Explosive, Modified Arsenal of ''Doom''|first=Matt|last=Bertz|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany enemies also return from the original game, such as the Revenant, Pinky, Mancubus, and [[Cyberdemon]], with many also redesigned.<ref name=gr-doom-development>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-4-review/?|title=Doom is fast, thrilling, authentic, and deeply, hilariously gory|first=David|last=Houghton |date=July 3, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[GamesRadar]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707074519/http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-4-review/|archivedate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> ''Doom''{{'}}s campaign was made to be at least 13 hours long, and the \"Ultra-Nightmare\" difficulty level features [[permadeath]], which causes the savegame to be lost once the player dies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dooms-campaign-is-about-13-hours-dev-says/1100-6434816/|title=Doom's Campaign Is About 13 Hours, Dev Says|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|publisher=GameSpot|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ign.com/articles/2016/04/28/nobody-has-beaten-dooms-hardest-difficulty-level|title=Nobody Has Beaten Doom's Hardest Difficulty Level|first=Jared|last=Petty|publisher=IGN|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref> The campaign also features 13 levels.<ref name=13-secret>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94931/doom-how-to-find-all-13-classic-maps|title=''Doom'': How to Find All 13 Classic Maps|first=Cassidee|last=Moser|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 30, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of the levels have multiple pathways and open areas, which allow players to explore and find collectibles and secrets throughout the levels. Many of these collectibles can be used as part of ''Doom''{{'}}s progression system, including weapon mods, rune powers, and Praetor Suit upgrades. Weapon points come from field drones and allow the player to unlock alternate modes of fire for many weapons, such as explosive shots and different rate and output of firepower. Each of the weapons' firing modes can be further upgraded using weapon tokens, but they can only be maxed out by completing a challenge related to that particular firing mode. Runes transport the player to a separate arena to perform a combat challenge that grants different abilities when successfully completed, such as better equipment drops from fallen enemies. Players can also upgrade their \"Praetor Suit\" by retrieving special tokens from dead marines and using them to improve functionality such as equipment, navigation and resistances.<ref name=pg-custom>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/11/11657360/doom-trailer-campaign-progression-system|title=''Doom'' developers explain the campaign's progression system|first=Samit|last=Sarkar|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref> Other pickups include small [[Doomguy]] figurines that allow the player to view 3D models of different characters, and data files that expand on the characters and story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/05/surprise-dooms-campaign-is-actually-fun/|title=Surprise, DOOM's Campaign Is Actually Fun|first=Alex|last=Walker|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, each of the game's levels contains a hidden lever which opens an area extracted from a classic level in the original ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' or ''[[Doom II]]''. Finding each of these areas unlocks them, making them accessible from the game's main menu in a section called ''Classic Maps''.<ref name=13-secret/>\n\n===Multiplayer===\nIn ''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer mode, several modes, such as team [[deathmatch]] and its variation \"Soul Harvest\", as well as Freeze Tag, Warpath ([[King of the Hill (game)|King of the Hill]] with a moving 'hill'), Domination, and \"Clan Arena\" (team [[Last man standing (video games)|last man standing]] with no pickups), exist within the game.<ref name=gem_e3>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/06/doom-unveiled-coming-spring-2016|title=Doom unveiled, coming spring 2016|first=Sal|last=Romano|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=June 5, 2016|website=Gematsu}}</ref> Players can also use power-ups and teleporters in a multiplayer match. They can pick up a Demon Rune, one of the power-ups featured, to transform into and fight as a demon. There are four demons available initially in the game, each of which has different abilities: the Revenant, the Baron of Hell, the Mancubus, and the Prowler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-03-25-doom-details-its-four-playable-demons|title=''Doom'' details its four playable demons|first=Jeffrey|last=Matulef|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 25, 2016|accessdate=June 21, 2016}}</ref> At launch, the game featured nine maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/new-doom-teaser-showcases-nine-multiplayer-maps/?|title=New Doom teaser showcases nine multiplayer maps|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPlayers are granted [[experience point]]s upon each match. After they have collected sufficient experience points, players can level up, by which new armor, skins, weapons, and power-ups would be unlocked for players to use. Both the player character and weapon can be customized extensively by applying new skins and colors onto them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-multiplayer-progression-armor/|title=Doom character customization mixes Call of Duty and a ton of armor|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In addition, players can receive hack modules while playing the game, which are special abilities that can only be used once after they are collected. There are over six types of modules. Scout reveals the locations of all enemies to the player for a limited time after respawning, while Vital Signs shows all enemies' health. Retribution allows players to track their last killer by revealing that player's health and location, while Power Seeker guides players to the power weapon pickup in the game. The Resupply Timer, meanwhile, shows the respawn time of the power-up items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/dooms-hack-modules-will-offer-temporary-multiplayer-boosts/|title=Doom's Hack Modules will offer temporary multiplayer boosts|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|date=February 22, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> Players can also perform taunts in the game's multiplayer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-03-30-yes-you-can-do-the-carlton-dance-in-the-new-doom|title=Yes, you can do the Carlton dance in the new Doom|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 30, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, Update 6.66 was released for ''Doom''<nowiki/>'s multiplayer. Update 6.66 features a revised progression system, all three DLC bundled into the core game, a new 'rune' system (replacing the Hack Module system) and enhanced kill notifications. To accommodate this new progression system, Update 6.66 also reset all players' multiplayer experience progression, but not without giving players the option whether to retain all unlocked items or reset them. Players who played before Update 6.66 and players who obtained the 'Slayer' level received unique medals to show their status.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3lw31bjKOsagegSyIYWIEg/the-ultimate-doom-update-6-66-all-dlc-unlocked-free-weekends|title=The \u2018Ultimate\u2019 DOOM \u2013 Update 6.66, All DLC Unlocked, Free Weekends|last=Stratton|first=Marty|date=|work=|access-date=July 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Level creation tool===\nIn all of its platforms except the Nintendo Switch, ''Doom'' includes a built-in [[Level editor|level creation tool]] called \"SnapMap\" which allows players to create and edit maps with their own structure and game logic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/14/8779769/doom-snapmap-pc-ps4-xbox-one|title=Doom SnapMap lets users create and share their own gameplay modes|first=Samit|last=Sarker|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> With SnapMap, players can create maps for different modes, ranging from single-player levels to co-operative or competitive multiplayer maps. When players are building a level, the game will shift to a top-down view. Players can place rooms and hallways to form a level and connect them together. If they are not connected together, the color of the construction pieces changes to notify the player. Players can also use the X-ray camera which temporarily removes all the walls to allow players to view the objects inside. Players can also place enemies into their maps, with the exception of the campaign's [[boss (video games)|bosses]]. Their [[artificial intelligence]] and stats, and the player's own movement speed can also be modified. Players can also add additional particle effects, lighting effects, and other gameplay items, such as health packs and ammo pick-ups.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\"/> Only in-game assets can be used, and players cannot create or import their own models into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/05/20/doom-snapmap-review/|title=DOOM SnapMap: A Brilliant & Accessible Modding Tool With Infuriating Restrictions|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Levels can be tested before they are published online.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\"/>\n\nFor players who do not wish to create extensively, the game features an AI conductor which automatically generates enemies.<ref name=\"SnapMapInfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/29/doom-snapmap-hands-on.aspx|title=Hands On With Doom's SnapMap|first=Andrew|last=Reiner|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=January 29, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Players receive \"snap points\" after they create a level or play a level created by other users. These points can be used to unlock additional cosmetic items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-snapmap-toolset-showcased-in-lengthy-dev-video/|title=Doom SnapMap toolset showcased in lengthy dev video|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=April 26, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Players can share their completed maps with other players. They can vote on and even modify other players' content and share them while citing the originals' authors.<ref name=gi-snapmap-easy>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/27/infinite-doom-why-snapmap-is-id-s-secret-weapon.aspx|title=Infinite ''Doom'': Why SnapMap Is id's Secret Weapon|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''Doom'' takes place during the year 2162{{efn|Although the year is never specified in the game, its sequel, ''[[Doom Eternal]]'', is set in 2163, specifying a eight month gap from the events of the 2016 game.}} in a research facility on Mars owned by the Union Aerospace Corporation, run by Dr. Samuel Hayden, a UAC scientist whose mind now inhabits an android body after having lost his original to brain cancer. Researchers at the UAC facility have attempted to draw energy from Hell, an alternative dimension inhabited by demons, in order to solve an energy crisis on Earth using the Argent Tower, which siphons energy and allows travel to and from Hell.<ref name=vb-plot>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/05/27/the-deanbeat-doom-is-a-memorable-trip-back-into-shooting-hell/|title=''The DeanBeat'': ''Doom'' is a memorable trip back into shooting hell|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> To supplement their work, Hayden organizes several expeditions into Hell, bringing back captive demons and artifacts for study. Among them is a [[sarcophagus]] containing the [[Doomguy|Doom Slayer]] (along with his Praetor Suit), who the demons imprisoned after his earlier rampage through Hell.\n\nThe facility is overrun by demons after one of Hayden's researchers, Olivia Pierce, makes a pact with them and uses the Tower to open a portal to Hell.<ref name=vb-plot/> In desperation, Hayden releases the Doom Slayer from his sarcophagus to repel the demonic invasion and close the portal. The Doom Slayer recovers his Praetor Suit and fights his way through the overrun facility, where he realigns a comms satellite dish to get a lay of the land, all guided by the AI VEGA. After clearing out the facility core and preventing a meltdown, he pursues Pierce as she destroys the energy induction filters to Hayden's objections. He pursues Pierce up the tower, where she uses an Argent accumulator to open an explosive rift into Hell, destroying the Tower, and where the Slayer is sent back. \n\nFighting his way to a teleporter, the Doom Slayer returns to Mars and makes his way to a tram leading to Hayden. Hayden informs the Slayer of the Helix Stone, an artifact used to study and harness Hell's energy. Entering the Lazarus labs, he observes the Helix Stone, and he learns of the Well, where the portal is powered, and of the magical key-like blade, the Crucible. He makes another excursion into Hell after battling and defeating a contained Cyberdemon and activating its accumulator, and fights through a labyrinthine gauntlet to recover the Crucible from a trio of Hell Guards. Arriving at VEGA's facility in the frozen north, he destroys the AI (while also making a backup copy), using its power to enter the Well, where he uses the Crucible to destroy the portal's power source. Finally, he confronts Pierce, who is transformed by the demons into the monstrous Spider Mastermind, and kills her.\n\nUpon the Doom Slayer's return to Mars, Hayden confiscates the Crucible, which he plans to use in his research. Despite all that has happened, he insists that Earth is too desperate for energy to give up. To keep the Doom Slayer from interfering with his plans, Hayden teleports him to an undisclosed location, saying that they [[Doom Eternal|will meet again]].\n\n==Development==\n===As ''Doom 4''===\n[[File:A screenshot of the canned Doom 4.jpg|thumb|A screenshot of the canceled ''Doom 4'', which showcased a more urban environment than its predecessors]]\n\n[[John Carmack]], co-founder of and then lead developer at [[id Software]], indicated that ''Doom 4'' was in development at [[QuakeCon]] on August 3, 2007.<ref name=\"carmackrage\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200708/N07.0803.1731.12214.htm?Page=2|title=QuakeCon 2007: John Carmack Talks ''Rage'', Id Tech 5 And More|last=Berghammer|first=Billy|date=August 3, 2007|work=Game Informer|accessdate=August 24, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029050912/http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200708/N07.0803.1731.12214.htm?Page=2|archivedate=October 29, 2007}}</ref> It was announced in May 2008.<ref name=\"ign_announce\">{{cite web |last=Ocampo |first=Jason |date=May 7, 2008 |accessdate=May 7, 2008 |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/872/872097p1.html |title=''Doom 4'' Announced|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> Id Software CEO [[Todd Hollenshead]] suggested that like ''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]'', the game would take place on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/DOOM-4-Rage-FPS-John-Carmack-id-Tech-5,14837.html|title=Are These Really ''Doom 4'' Screenshots?|first=Kevin|last=Parrish|work=[[Tom's Hardware]]|publisher=[[Purch Group]]|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> Carmack stated that it would feature gameplay more akin to the original ''Doom'' games rather than the [[survival horror]] gameplay of ''[[Doom 3]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/85484-John-Carmack-Sheds-Some-Light-On-Doom-4 |title=John Carmack Sheds Some Light On Doom 4 |first=Andy|last=Chalk|date=August 6, 2008|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Carmack claimed that Doom 4 would look \"three times better\" than ''[[Rage (video game)|Rage]]'' even though it was intended to run at 30 frames per second on Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, rather than the 60 that ''Rage'' was targeting.<ref name=1up-new>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/doom-game-announced|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714131428/http://www.1up.com/news/doom-game-announced|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 14, 2012|title=Next ''Doom'' Game Announced|first=Philip|last=Kollar|work=[[1UP.com|1UP]]|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=July 31, 2008|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> It was planned to run at 60 frames per second on Windows with state-of-the-art hardware.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.maximumpc.com/article/news/quakecon_08_quake_live_will_have_no_mod_support_doom_4_run_60hz_pc_locked_30hz_consoles | title=QuakeCon 08: Quake Live Will Have No Mod Support; Doom 4 to Run at 60Hz on PC, Locked at 30Hz for Consoles |date=July 31, 2008 |first=Norman|last=Chan|publisher=[[Maximum PC]]|accessdate=November 30, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628192231/http://www.maximumpc.com/article/news/quakecon_08_quake_live_will_have_no_mod_support_doom_4_run_60hz_pc_locked_30hz_consoles|archivedate=June 28, 2011}}</ref> Carmack also stated that the game was running on the [[id Tech 5]] game engine.<ref name=1up-new/> In 2009, he revealed that the multiplayer component was being developed separately and would run at 60 frames per second.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N_Ge-35Ld70 | title=John Carmack on Rage |date=July 2009 |work=[[YouTube]]|publisher=CD-Action |accessdate=October 30, 2010}}</ref> He stated in 2011 that \"you can't have 30 guys crawling all over you at 60 frames per second at this graphics technology level because it's painful.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6318725/e3-2011-john-carmack-talks-wii-u-playstation-vita-and-next-gen-rage |title=E3 2011: John Carmack talks Wii U, PlayStation Vita, and next-gen Rage|date=June 9, 2011|first=Tor|last=Thorsen|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=June 9, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128080308/http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6318725/e3-2011-john-carmack-talks-wii-u-playstation-vita-and-next-gen-rage|archivedate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, Hollenshead said that ''Doom 4'' was \"deep in development\". Asked whether ''Doom 4'' would be a sequel, a reboot, or a prequel, his response was \"It's not a sequel to ''Doom 3'', but it's not a reboot either. ''Doom 3'' was sort of a reboot. It's a little bit different than those.\"<ref name=\"GameSpotApr09Doom4\">{{cite web|last=Thorsen |first=Tor |date=April 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 10, 2009 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6207773.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=topstory&tag=topstory;title |title=Hollenshead Rages about PC gaming, E3 surprises|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104071832/http://www.gamespot.com/news/hollenshead-rages-about-pc-gaming-e3-surprises-6207773|archivedate=November 4, 2012}}</ref> On June 23, 2009, [[ZeniMax Media]], parent company of [[Bethesda Softworks]], acquired id Software and announced that future id games would be published by Bethesda Softworks, including ''Doom 4''.<ref name=\"doompublisher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6243433.html/ |title=Bethesda publishing Rage |last=Magrino |first= Tom |date=December 15, 2009 |work=GameSpot |accessdate=March 1, 2014 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091218064325/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6243433.html |archivedate = December 18, 2009}}</ref> Id Software creative director [[Tim Willits]] announced that key releases would be much sooner and that the partnership allowed id Software to have two teams, each having a project in parallel development, for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/08/16/doom-4-coming-sooner-than-you-think|title=''Doom 4'' Coming Sooner Than You Think|first=Jim|last=Reilly|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> Carmack added that, once ''Rage'' was complete, its development team would move to ''Doom 4''. ''Doom 4'' might also feature dedicated servers unlike ''Rage''.<ref name=\"Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4zgYG-_ha28|title=Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011 |date=August 5, 2011|author=QuakeCon Official|publisher=[[ZeniMax Media]]|work=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2011 QuakeCon, Carmack mentioned that the new ''Doom'' would be using a new scripting language based on [[C++]] and called it \"super-script\", a superset of C++ with features such as scheduling and [[type safety]].<ref name=\"Carmack's Keynote at QuakeCon 2011\" /> At the end of 2012, the team decided to make ''Doom 4'' a reboot.<ref name=metro-interview>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/07/02/doom-id-software-interview-they-just-love-blowing-up-barrels-5276385/|title=''Doom'' id Software interview \u2013 \u2018They just love blowing up barrels!\u2019|first=David|last=Jenkins|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|date=July 2, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> In November 2013, Carmack left id Software to commit to his work at [[Oculus Rift|Oculus VR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/11/22/john-carmack-leaves-id-software-to-focus-on-oculus-vr/|title=John Carmack leaves id Software to focus on Oculus VR|first=Jon|last=Fingas|date=November 22, 2013|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]}}</ref>\n\n{{quotebox|quote=\"Every game has a soul. Every game has a spirit. When you played ''Rage'', you got the spirit. And [''Doom 4''] did not have the spirit, it did not have the soul, it didn't have a personality.\"|author=Tim Willits|source=[[QuakeCon]] 2013<ref name=ign-character/>|width=20%}}\n\nIn April 2013, [[Kotaku]] published an [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9]] describing ''Doom 4'' as trapped in \"[[development hell]]\". Citing connections to id, the article claimed that ''Doom 4'' had suffered under mismanagement and that development was completely restarted in 2011. Inside sources described the pre-2011 version \u2013 which was to portray the uprising of Hell on Earth \u2013 as heavily [[Scripted sequence|scripted]] and cinematic, comparing it to the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' franchise. The pre-2011 version was criticized as mediocre and the new version as \"lame\" and a \"mess\".<ref name=\"kotaku.com\">{{cite web|last=Schreier |first=Jason |url=http://kotaku.com/five-years-and-nothing-to-show-how-doom-4-got-off-trac-468097062 |title=Five Years And Nothing To Show: How Doom 4 Got Off Track |publisher=[[Kotaku]] |date=April 3, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> While Hollenshead initially stated that the ''Doom 4'' team was doing something that fans would be happy with,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-04-19-doom-fans-will-be-happy-with-doom-4|title=''Doom'' fans \"will be happy\" with ''Doom 4''|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> Id's Willits criticized the game's lack of character in QuakeCon 2013.<ref name=ign-character>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/02/id-software-pushing-boundaries-focusing-only-on-doom-4|title=id Software 'Pushing Boundaries,' Focusing Only on Doom 4|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=August 2, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref> In July 2015, Marty Stratton criticized ''Doom 4''{{'}}s lack of personality as id's primary reason to cancel the game, and pointed out its similarities to the ''Call of Duty'' franchise and that the game was not the product that id thought people wanted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/call-doom-died-because-it-didnt-match-game-we-think-you-wanted-play/|title=''Call of DOOM'' died because it \"didnt match the game we thought people wanted\"|first=Leon|last=Hurley|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 video documentary by [[Noclip]], ''Doom'' creative director Hugo Martin described the \"Hell on Earth\" premise as: \"It was like [[Robert Zemeckis]]. See [[Contact (1997 American film)|''Contact'']], like, if this really happened. Now let's be clear: it was awesome. But it was more realistic. It was about the global impact of a Hellish invasion.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=[[Noclip]]|title=DOOM Resurrected - To Hell & Back (DOOM Documentary)|date=December 12, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PS6SBnccxMA|accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The creative director of the ''Doom 4'' prototype, [[Kevin Cloud]], said in the same interview, \"As far as the upper-level creative direction, that was me driving that. And honestly, again, taking it in a direction I don't think the fans would have enjoyed.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===As ''Doom''===\nAfter the game's redesign began, Willits revealed in August 2013 that ''Doom'' was still the team's focus.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-4-still-exists-bethesda-unveils-doom-beta/1100-6417840/ |title=Doom 4 still exists: Bethesda unveils Doom beta|first=Martin|last=Gaston|work=[[GameSpot]] |date=February 19, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2015}}</ref> British science fiction writer [[Graham Joyce]] was enlisted to write the game's story; after Joyce died in 2014, Adam Gascoine was brought in as a replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/23/11745422/how-doom-lived-up-to-nearly-a-decades-worth-of-expectations|title=How ''Doom'' lived up to nearly a decade's worth of expectations (update)|first=Brian|last=Crecente|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> Sound designer Chad Mossholder was recruited to write flavor text, after the team found out he writes [[comic]]s.<ref>https://www.shacknews.com/article/99662/stairway-to-badass-the-making-and-remaking-of-doom?page=4</ref>\n\nA [[teaser trailer]] of ''Doom'' was presented at [[E3 2014]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/conferences/e32014/11630-Doom-Reboot-Revealed-by-Bethesda|title=''Doom'' Reboot Revealed by Bethesda|first=Steven|last=Bogos|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and on the QuakeCon and ''Doom'' websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doom.com/en-us/|title=''DOOM'' official website|publisher=[[id Software]]|accessdate=June 11, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611054229/http://doom.com/en-us/|archivedate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> A more expansive trailer was unveiled at QuakeCon 2014 on July 17, wherein a closed presentation was made mainly to silence ongoing rumors of the project being in jeopardy.<ref name=quakecon>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-was-revealed-to-counter-fears-of-trouble-at-id-software-public-reveal-unlikely-this-year/|title=Doom was revealed to counter fears of trouble at id Software, public reveal unlikely this year|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2016}}</ref> Id Software executive producer Marty Stratton, the host of the presentation, announced that ''Doom 4'' had been renamed ''Doom'' as \"it\u2019s an origin game, reimagining everything about the originals\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2014/07/18/doom-4-details-quakecon-2014-reboot/|title=Why id Software is calling it \"Doom\" and not \"Doom 4\"|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref> In light of [[Crytek]]'s financial difficulties, it was announced that Tiago Sousa, head R&D graphics engineer at Crytek, was leaving to join the ''Doom'' and id Tech 6 engine team as a lead programmer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/07/19/eleven-year-crytek-engineer-veteran-joins-id-software/|title=Eleven year Crytek engineer veteran joins id Software|first=Thomas|last=Schulenberg|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Games Industry International]]|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quotebox|align=left|quote=It all kind of gets tossed into a big pot of soup, and you're saying, \"Does it feel fun, or does it not feel fun?\", and then you make your decisions along those lines, but I think [the progression system]'ll be an important part of ''Doom'', and I think people will be excited about it when they get a sense of what we're doing.|author=Marty Stratton|source=''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''<ref name=pg-multi/>|width=20%}}\nBethesda released a teaser trailer to promote gameplay being shown at [[E3 2015]] on June 14, 2015; the trailer depicted the double-barreled shotgun and the Revenant, a monster returning to the game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-18-a-very-brief-look-at-the-new-doom | title=A (very) brief look at the new Doom |first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]] | publisher=Gamer Network | date=May 18, 2015 | accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> On June 14, around 15 minutes of gameplay footage were shown at E3.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pitcher |first=Jenna |date=June 14, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/15/e3-2015-doom-release-date-announced |title=E3 2015: DOOM Release Date Announced |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Regarding the progression system, Marty Stratton thought that it was important to allow players personalization and customization.<ref name=pg-multi>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/23/9027433/doom-4-multiplayer-preview-gameplay-loadouts-unlocks|title=''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer mixes modern and retro, but it's still the fastest game in town|first=Griffin|last=McElroy|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nid felt the greatest challenge was to compete with other first-person shooters such as ''[[Call of Duty]]'' and ''[[Battlefield (video game series)|Battlefield]],'' as younger players were less familiar with the older ''Doom'' franchise. They also found it difficult to establish a game with its own identity while \"being faithful\" to other games in the series. The team consulted the game directors at [[Bethesda Game Studios]], who Stratton considered \"[had gone] through the same thing when they were working on ''[[Fallout 3]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-devs-talk-challenges-of-rebooting-the-series/1100-6429176/|title=Doom Devs Talk Challenges of Rebooting the Series|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Doom 2016 reversible cover.jpeg|thumb|250px|This cover is similar to and inspired by the original game's cover art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/03/07/hated-doom-39-s-cover-vote-for-your-reverse-sleeve-pick.aspx|title=[Update] A Winner Has Been Named In ''Doom'' Alternate Art Vote|first=Jeff|last=Cork|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> After being favored by fans, and in response to criticisms of the primary cover, this reversible cover was elected to be the official one. It was used later by the [[Nintendo Switch]] port as the default box art.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=DOOM|number=908386725860388864|date=September 13, 2017|title=From Mars, to Hell, to the palm of your hand. DOOM arrives on NintendoSwitch in Holiday 2017!}}</ref>]]\n\nOn July 2, 2015, Stratton revealed that the game would not take place on Earth and that, unlike ''Doom 3,'' the game was comic and \"very juvenile\".<ref name=metro-interview/> Director Hugo Martin later said that the game was heavily inspired by [[rock and roll]] and ''[[He-Man and the Masters of the Universe]]'' and that its Hell-themed levels would feature much [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]]. ''Doom''{{'}}s world was designed to have personality and be \"over the top\"; the UAC industrial field was designed to be the massive underbelly of the corporation, the UAC corporate field zone was designed to be much cleaner in terms of splattered goriness than the other zones to prevent repetition. Skulls were used in Hell as iconic elements and the Titan's Realm zone was constructed from dead, ancient, colossal demons.<ref name=gi-gruesome/> At QuakeCon 2015, it was announced that the game would run at 1080p and 60 frames per second on console, as id considered it \"the most necessary graphical goal\" which could effectively improve gameplay fluidity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-dev-we-want-to-be-the-best-looking-game-out-t/1100-6429178/|title=Doom Dev: \"We Want to Be the Best-Looking Game Out There at 60 FPS and 1080p\"|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 25, 2015|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref> According to Martin, the team put little emphasis on story, as they believed that it was not an important feature of the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-is-totally-rock-n-roll-dev-says/1100-6433576/|title=Doom Is Totally Rock 'N Roll, Dev Says|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Instead, they added codex items to let interested players speculate about the story and the identity of the player character.<ref name=\"Jason-O'Connell\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/07/02/how-doom-tells-players-part-of-the-story-and-leaves-them-guessing/|title=How ''Doom'' reveals its secrets like a ''Frank Frazetta'' painting|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=July 2, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Stratton and Martin, movement is the game's most important pillar. To help keep movement fast, weapon reloading was excluded and levels were designed to discourage players from hiding.<ref name=glory-kills>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/18/see-how-id-39-s-new-doom-breaks-the-modern-shooter-mold.aspx|title=See How id's New ''Doom'' Breaks The Modern Shooter Mold|first=Wade|last=Wojcik|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> On January 25, Stratton confirmed the game's feature of nonlinear exploration and stated that combat is the game's focus and that the difficulty of the game was raised with the aim of creating an ultimate first-person shooter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/637803/Doom-Update-PS4-Xbox-One-Difficulty-Level-Non-Linear-Exploration-Confirmed|title=''Doom'' update: Late changes made as non-linear exploration is confirmed|first=Anthony|last=Chapman|work=[[Daily Express]]|publisher=[[Express Newspapers]]|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, 2016, the release date of the ''Doom'' beta, a cinematic trailer directed by [[Joe Kosinski]] was created to evoke the game's three core pillars: incessant combat, terrifying demons, and powerful guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-doom-live-action-trailer-from-tron-legacy-di/1100-6436174/|title=Watch ''Doom'' Live-Action Trailer From Tron: Legacy Director|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Doom''{{'}}s [[multiplayer]] was developed in conjunction with [[Certain Affinity]].<ref name=ca-multi>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-new-doom-multiplayer-trailer-closed-beta-dat/1100-6435474/|title=Watch New ''Doom'' Multiplayer Trailer, Closed Beta Dates Announced For PS4, Xbox One, and PC|first=Zorine|last=Te|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=March 9, 2016|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> SnapMap was developed in conjunction with [[Escalation Studios]] and designed to be powerful,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escalation.com/project/doom|title=DOOM Escalation Studios|website=Escalation Studios|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> to give players the opportunity to create their own content as part of the ''Doom'' and id legacies, and target those who have no experience or expertise in traditional [[Mod (video games)|modding]].<ref name=gi-snapmap-easy/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/264518/Dooms_usergen_mode_SnapMap_Its_not_mods_but_heres_what_it_is.php|title=''Doom''{{'}}s user-gen mode, SnapMap: It's not mods, but here's what it ''is''|first=Christian|last=Nutt|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM plc|UBM]]|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\nThe ''Doom'' soundtrack was composed by [[Mick Gordon (composer)|Mick Gordon]], with additional contributions by [[Richard Devine]]. Gordon aimed to treat the game's original soundtrack with \"utmost respect\" while modernizing it; however, the team at id stipulated in the initial brief that they wanted \"no guitars\" on the soundtrack, fearing that it would make the game \"feel like ''[[Bill & Ted]]''\"<ref name=\"noclipMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r0nOsuaPDeg|title=DOOM Documentary: Part 3 - Guns, Guitars & Chess on Mars|first=|last=[[Noclip]]|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and that [[heavy metal music]] itself has become \"a bit of a joke\".<ref name=\"GDCMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U4FNBMZsqrY|title=DOOM: Behind the Music|first=|last=GDC|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> Gordon's initial concept was based around the idea of Argent energy corrupting human-made devices; to mirror this in music, he fed basic waveforms \u2013 [[sine wave]]s and [[white noise]] \u2013 through a complex array of [[effects unit]]s such as distortion and compression.<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> While this resulted in a unique electronic sound, the game still wasn't \"sounding like ''Doom''\"; Gordon then gradually started adding more and more guitar elements, which eventually resulted in the desired tone and feel for the game; Gordon used [[seven-string guitar|seven-]] and [[eight-string guitar]]s to give the music a lower tone, and used a [[nine-string guitar]] for the game's main theme, a variation on [[Bobby Prince]]'s \"E1M1\" / \"At DOOM's Gate\" theme;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ua-f0ypVbPA|title=''DOOM'': Behind The Music Part 1|first=Mick|last=Gordon|work=[[YouTube]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=June 5, 2016}}</ref> Gordon would eventually admit that using a nine-string was \"kinda stupid\" in its excess, and that while he eventually sold the guitar to [[Fredrik Thordendal]] from [[Meshuggah]], \"even he can't find a use for it\".<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> The soundtrack contains numerous [[easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s: some songs reference themes or sounds from older ''Doom'' games, others contain [[backmasking]] (\"Jesus loves you\"), images of pentagrams and the number 666 embedded into the sound via [[steganography]]. Gordon intended these as a joke, and never thought anyone would find them,<ref name=\"GDCMusic\"/> but they were discovered shortly after release and widely covered in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/31/11825606/doom-2016-soundtrack-satan-666-inverted-pentagram|title=Satanic figures are hidden in Doom's soundtrack|first=Nick|last=Statt|date=May 31, 2016|website=The Verge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/doom-soundtrack-includes-satanic-messages-hidden-in-the-game-s-audio-a7057261.html|title=There are terrifying, satanic messages hidden in the Doom soundtrack|date=May 31, 2016|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/dooms-soundtrack-hides-a-satanic-easter-egg-1779657359|title=Doom's Soundtrack Hides A Satanic Easter Egg|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|website=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack was widely praised and won the Best Music / Sound Design award at [[The Game Awards 2016]]; Gordon, joined by [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]] drummer Matt Halpern and ''[[Quake II]]'' composer [[Sascha Dikiciyan]] (aka Sonic Mayhem), performed a short medley of the soundtracks \"Rip and Tear\" and \"BFG Division\" as well as ''Quake II''{{'}}s \"Descent Into Cerberon\" live at the awards show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/12/2/13815036/watch-the-doom-soundtrack-live-the-game-awards-2016|title=performed live at The Game Awards 2016|first=Ashley|last=Oh|date=December 2, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2012|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> The soundtrack was released in September 2016. It contains 31 tracks from the game, over 2 hours of music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/09/doom-reboots-killer-dynamic-soundtrack-has-finally-been-sequenced-as-an-lp/|title=Rip and tear your eardrums with Doom 2016\u2019s soundtrack, finally loosed from the game|first=Sam|last=Machkovech|work=[[Ars Technica]]|date=September 28, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release and marketing==\n\n\nOn February 19, 2014, Bethesda revealed that access to a beta version of ''Doom 4'', titled ''Doom'', would be available for those who pre-ordered ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'' on any of the supportable platforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bethblog.com/2014/02/19/get-psyched-wolfenstein-release-date-first-details-on-doom-beta/ |title=''Wolfenstein: The New Order'' Out 5/20, Pre-order for ''Doom'' Beta Access|first=Matt|last=Grandstaff|work=[[PlayStation Blog]]|publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]]|date=February 19, 2014|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> Those players were also eligible for selection to participate in the game's multiplayer-only limited alpha, which ran between December 3 and 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/bethesda-to-host-limited-doom-multiplayer-alpha-in-the-coming-months-3422123|title=Bethesda to host limited DOOM multiplayer alpha 'in the coming months'|first=Jordan|last=Biazzo|work=[[Gamereactor]]|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref> The beta began on March 31, 2016, and ended on April 3.<ref name=ca-multi/> It was followed by an open beta, which started on April 15, 2016, and ended on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/06/doom-open-beta-april-15th/|title='Doom' open beta kicks off April 15th|first=Jon|last=Fingas|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' was released for [[Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] on May 13, 2016, worldwide; an exception was Japan, where it was released on May 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/05/12/doom-heres-the-pc-requirements-and-launch-times-for-your-region/|title=''Doom'': here\u2019s the PC requirements and launch times for your region|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|publisher=[[VG247]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> It is also the first game of the ''Doom'' franchise to be released as uncensored in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/24/11105336/doom-uncut-german-release|title=''Doom'' launching uncut in Germany \u2014 a franchise first|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Bethesda partnered with [[Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsports]] for a special promotion that had [[Mikhail Aleshin]] driving a ''Doom''-styled car at the [[Indianapolis 500]] racing competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-branded-car-will-race-at-indy-500/1100-6439741/|title=Doom-Branded Car Will Race at Indy 500|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 23, 2016, ''Doom'' was made available for Xbox One owners to pre-order; for a limited time, they would also get the two original games, ''Doom'' and ''Doom II'', for free. Other bonuses included the Demon Multiplayer Pack, which offered a demon-themed armor set with three skin variations; six metallic paint colors and three id Software logo patterns used for character customization; and six sets of consumable Hack Module perks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/23/11098920/doom-pre-orders-backward-compatible-doom-free-xbox-one|title=''Doom'' pre-orders on Xbox come with original games for free|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 23, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/original-doom-doom-ii-xbox-one-doom-pre-order-bonus/|title=Get the original ''Doom'' and ''Doom II'' free by pre-ordering the Xbox One version of ''Doom''|first=Kristofer|last=Wouk|publisher=[[Digital Trends]]|date=February 23, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> There is also a Collector's Edition, which was significantly more expensive than the normal edition. It includes a figurine of the Revenant \u2013 a demon featured in the game \u2013 and a metal case.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/doom-release-date-120-collectors-edition-announced/1100-6434481/|title=Doom Release Date, $120 Collector's Edition Announced|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=February 4, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nid Software replaced Certain Affinity to work on the multiplayer for Windows after the game's launch and promised to fix its issues and introduced new features such as private matches, custom game settings and an enhanced cheat detection system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/doom-s-multiplayer-is-being-taken-over-by-id-who-promises-to-fix-things-367266.phtml|title=Doom's multiplayer is being taken over by id, who promises to fix things|first=Brett|last=Makedonski|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016|work=[[Destructoid]]}}</ref> At [[E3 2016]] on June 12, Bethesda Softworks announced its division, Bethesda VR, and that it was working on [[virtual reality]] support for the newly-released ''Doom'', set for release on an unspecified date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/06/13/doom-fallout-creator-dives-into-virtual-reality.html|title=''Doom'', ''Fallout'' creator dives into virtual reality|first=Chris|last=Morris|work=[[CNBC]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=June 13, 2016|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> Also at E3 2016 on that day, Bethesda Softworks and id Software announced the game's free demo, which was initially going to last for only a week but was extended indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-extends-free-doom-demo/|title=Bethesda extends free Doom demo|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=June 21, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> They also announced new multiplayer [[downloadable content]] titled ''Unto the Evil'', whose features include three maps and a new demon called the \"Harvester\", gun, equipment item, taunts, and armor sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2016/06/doom-unto-evil-multiplayer-dlc-announced|title=''Doom Unto the Evil'' multiplayer DLC announced|first=Sal|last=Romano|publisher=Gematsu|date=June 12, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> The DLC was released on August 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-08-04-dooms-unto-the-evil-dlc-is-now-available|title=Surprise! Doom's Unto the Evil DLC is now available|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=August 4, 2016|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Patch (computing)|Patch]]es for ''Doom'' were released after the game's release; these patches introduced a new photo mode, classic weapon pose,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-01-watch-the-new-dooms-classic-screen-centred-weapon-pose-in-action|title=Watch the new Doom's classic screen-centred weapon pose in action|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=July 1, 2016|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> and support for the [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]] API.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ryan|title=Doom Vulkan Patch Released|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/10483/doom-vulkan-patch-released|accessdate=July 13, 2016|publisher=[[AnandTech]]|date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> The Vulkan patch was expected to enable playable frame rates on older hardware. Subsequent benchmarks show up to a 66% improvement in the frame rates on [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] graphics cards, with minor changes in the performance of [[Nvidia]] cards.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kampman|first1=Jeff|title=Report: Doom's Vulkan renderer proves a boon for Radeons|url=https://techreport.com/news/30385/report-doom-vulkan-renderer-proves-a-boon-for-radeons|accessdate=July 13, 2016|publisher=[[The Tech Report]]|date=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, an update was released which unlocked the game's premium multiplayer DLCs to all owners, while also revamping the progression system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3lw31bjKOsagegSyIYWIEg/the-ultimate-doom-update-6-66-all-dlc-unlocked-free-weekends|title=The 'Ultimate' DOOM \u2013 Update 6.66, All DLC Unlocked, Free Weekends|first=Marty|last=Stratton|website=Bethesda.net}}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2017, it was announced via Nintendo Direct that ''Doom'' would release on Nintendo Switch during the fourth quarter of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grant|first1=Christopher|title=Wolfenstein 2: The New Colossus and Doom coming to Nintendo Switch|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/9/13/16305008/wolfenstein-2-doom-nintendo-switch-release-date|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref> The retail Switch version differs from the other console versions in that the multiplayer component is not included in the base product, but is instead offered as a free download, whereas the SnapMap component is not included at all, both changes as a result of cartridge limitations.<ref name=\"Switchsnapmap\">{{cite web|last1=Matulef|first1=Jeffery|title=Doom on Switch won't have SnapMap level editor|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-09-15-doom-on-switch-wont-have-snapmap-level-editor|website=Eurogamer|date=|accessdate=September 16, 2017}}</ref> It was released on November 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dayus|first1=Oscar|title=Doom's Nintendo Switch Release Date Revealed|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/dooms-nintendo-switch-release-date-revealed/1100-6454094/|website=GameSpot|date=October 16, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> An update to the Switch version in February 2018 introduced the option to use the [[Motion controller|motion controls]] of the [[Joy-Con]]s for aiming, similar to other Switch games such as ''[[Splatoon 2]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kuchera|first1=Ben|title=Doom gets motion controls on the Nintendo Switch|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/2/20/17031590/doom-nintendo-switch-motion-controls|website=Polygon|date=February 20, 2018|accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMonths after ''Doom'' was released, [[Zen Studios]] developed a [[Pinball#Computer pinball simulation|virtual]] [[pinball]] adaptation of the game as part of the ''Bethesda Pinball'' collection, which became available as part of ''[[Zen Pinball 2]]'', ''[[Pinball FX 2]]''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coppock |first1=Mark |title=Now you can play pinball versions of Doom, Fallout, and Elder Scrolls |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/bethesda-pinball-released-for-pinball-fx2/ |website=DigitalTrends |accessdate=November 24, 2018 |date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Pinball FX 3]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/pinball-fx-3-is-all-about-cross-platform-competition-1797931064 | title = Pinball FX 3 Is All About Cross-Platform Competition | first = Mike | last = Fahey | date = August 17, 2017 | accessdate = August 17, 2017 | work = [[Kotaku]]}}</ref>  as well as a separate [[free-to-play]] app for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web |last1=BarbieBobomb |title=Bethesda and Zen Studios Team Up for an Epic Pinball Pack |url=https://blog.zenstudios.com/?p=6672 |website=[[Zen Studios]] |accessdate=November 24, 2018 |date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> At [[E3 2017]] Bethesda announced ''Doom VFR'', a [[virtual reality]] adaptation of ''Doom'', compatible with the [[PlayStation VR]] and [[HTC Vive]] headsets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-vfr-is-the-series-virtual-reality-debut/|title=Doom VFR is the series' virtual reality debut|date=June 11, 2017}}</ref> In ''Doom VFR'' the player assumes the role of Mars' last survivor who, after being killed, gets his consciousness uploaded into an artificial network, and is tasked with defeating the demons and restoring the facility's operations, having an array of electronic devices and weapons at his disposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/4KKxfa0osU6qSGQQwWqukY/from-mars-to-hell-in-doom-vfr|title=From Mars to Hell in DOOM VFR|website=Bethesda.net}}</ref> The game was released on December 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wccftech.com/skyrim-vr-doom-vfr-fallout-4-vr-release-dates-confirmed/|title=Skyrim VR, DOOM VFR And Fallout 4 VR Release Dates Confirmed|publisher=WCCFTech|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Pre-release===\nInitial reception of the QuakeCon 2014 trailer accumulated considerable acclaim among fans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2014/07/big-time-doom-fans-react-to-yesterdays-doom-reveal/|title=Big-Time ''Doom'' Fans React To Yesterday's ''Doom'' Reveal|first=Stephen|last=Totilo|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> and initial reception of the E3 2015 trailer was also positive, despite receiving criticisms by some critics, who considered the game to be too violent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/doom-launched-by-bethesda-at-e3-2015-swiftly-criticised-for-being-too-violent-10319985.html|title=Doom launched by Bethesda at E3 2015, swiftly criticised for being too violent|first=Andrew|last=Griffin|work=[[The Independent]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> Pete Hines from Bethesda Softworks responded by saying that the game is designed to allow players to apply violence on demons instead of humans. Hines added that, \"if you're not into [[graphic violence|violent, bloody]] games... ''Doom''{{'s}} probably not a game for you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/23/8833293/bethesda-had-the-perfect-answer-for-people-bothered-by-dooms-violence|title=Bethesda had the perfect answer for people bothered by Doom's violence: \u00af\\_(\u30c4)_/\u00af|first=Ben|last=Kuchera|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the open multiplayer beta, [[IGN]] writer Nathan Lawrence called the beta disappointing, considering it less of a classic style \"arena shooter\" and unfavorable compared to other shooters such as ''[[Halo (franchise)|Halo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/04/13/why-dooms-multiplayer-really-isnt-an-arena-shooter|title=Why Doom's Multiplayer Really Isn't An Arena Shooter|first=Nathan|last=Lawrence|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=May 8, 2016}}</ref> Similarly, the beta was negatively received by players on [[Steam (service)|Steam]], with mostly negative reviews at the time when the beta was active.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/04/doom-is-now-bethesdas-second-most-hated-game-on-steam/|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|title=DOOM Is Now Bethesda's Second Most Hated Game On Steam|date=April 18, 2016|first=Alex|last=Walker}}</ref> Rock, Paper, Shotgun writer Adam Smith found the beta both to be similar to games such as ''[[Quake 3]]'', ''[[Unreal Tournament]]'', and the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series and not to feel like ''Doom'' itself, and criticized the weapon loadout concept.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/04/15/doom-beta-review/|title=Impressions: Knee Deep In ''DOOM''{{'}}s Open Beta|first=Adam|last=Smith|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> Review copies of the game were held back until release day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/where-is-our-review-for-doom--360163.phtml|title=Where is our review for Doom?|last=Furniss|first=Zack|work=Destructoid|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-release===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = wikidata\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref name=\"destructoidreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-doom-361942.phtml|title=Doom Review \u2013 Rip and Tear|last=Furniss|first=Zack|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| EGM = 8.5/10<ref name=\"egmreview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Buchholtz|first=Matt|publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2016}}</ref>\n| GI = 8.75/10<ref name=\"gameinformerreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/doom/b/playstation4/archive/2016/05/17/doom-review.aspx|title=Doom Review \u2013 A Bloody Welcome Rebirth|last=Bertz|first=Matt|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"gamerevreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/doom-2016|title=Doom (2016) Review: A nostalgia filled gore-fest of a masterpiece!|last=Henriquez|first=Mike|work=[[Game Revolution]]|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gamespotreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-6416432/|title=Doom Review: Our hero who art in hell, cursed be thy name.|last=Brown|first=Peter|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"gamesradarreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doom-review/|title=Doom Review|last=Houghton|first=David|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=May 19, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| GB = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"giantbombreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/doom-review/1900-745/|title=Doom Review|last=Shoemaker|first=Brad|work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=May 21, 2016|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.1/10<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/16/doom-review-2?page=2?page=2 |title=Doom Review|last=Gilory|first=Joab|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 88/100<ref name=\"pcgamerreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/doom-review/|title=DOOM review|last=Davenport|first=James|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"polygonreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/18/11706108/doom-review-PC-xbox-one-PS4|title=DOOM review|last=Gies|first=Arthur|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"videogamer.comreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/doom_4_review.html|title=DOOM review (PS4)|last=Miller|first=Simon|work=VideoGamer.com|publisher=Candy Banana|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1=''[[Daily Express]]''\n|rev1Score={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=dereview/>\n|rev2=''[[Digital Spy]]''\n|rev2Score={{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"DigitalSpyreview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/review/a794296/doom-review-brtual-badass-and-so-close-to-the-doom-weve-always-wanted/|title=DOOM review: Brutal, badass and so close to the Doom reboot we always wanted|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n|rev3=''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n|rev3Score={{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=ttreview/>\n}}\n\n''Doom'' was released to positive reception regarding the fast-paced gameplay, single-player campaign, visuals and soundtrack whereas criticism was predominantly toward the multiplayer mode. Many critics believed that ''Doom'' was a successful return to form for the series. Following the wide release, the game received scores of 85/100 for PC and PlayStation 4 and 87/100 for the Xbox One on [[Metacritic]]. The Nintendo Switch edition, released in November 2017, was also positively received by professional reviewers, garnering a 79/100 on Metacritic: most reviewers praised the job of the port, also conceding that it's not as well-optimized as it was for previous consoles. The final version of the game received very positive reviews from users on [[Steam (service)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-05-18-the-new-doom-turns-around-steam-user-reviews|title=The new Doom campaign turns around Steam user reviews|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> It also received praise from other video game creators, including [[Cliff Bleszinski]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gears-of-war-designer-cliff-bleszinski-praises-new/1100-6439815/|title=Gears of War Designer Cliff Bleszinski Praises New Doom, But Has One Criticism|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref> and [[Greg Kasavin]], who said that the game answers questions that other modern shooters do not answer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/why-is-the-new-doom-so-important-it-asks-the-questions-other-shooters-aren-t-argues-supergiant-dev/0220857|title=Why is the new Doom so important? It asks the questions other shooters aren't, argues Supergiant dev|first=Matthew|last=Jarvis|work=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|date=May 26, 2016|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe game's single-player elements received critical acclaim. Alec Meer of Rock, Paper, Shotgun favorably compared ''Doom'' to the 2014 game ''[[Wolfenstein: The New Order]]'', also published by Bethesda, but added that ''Doom''{{'}}s quality surpassed that of ''Wolfenstein'' due to its fast pace and solid gunplay.<ref name=\"rockpapershotgun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/05/16/doom-review-pc/|title=Wot I Think: DOOM (Singleplayer)|last=Meer|first=Alec|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> Peter Brown of [[GameSpot]] praised single-player because he thought that the reboot captured the spirits of the older games, while refining them with modern elements. Brown also drew attention toward the soundtrack, calling it \"impactful\".<ref name=\"gamespotreview\"/> Gary Jones in the ''[[Daily Express]]'' felt that the game had one of the best single-player campaigns made for the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, successfully combining the traditional gameplay of the series with a very fast pace.<ref name=dereview>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/672439/DOOM-Review-Xbox-One-Bethesda-PS4|title=''DOOM'' Review: The best single-player FPS action on Xbox One and PS4|last=Jones|first=Gary|work=[[Daily Express]]|publisher=[[Express Newspapers]]|date=May 21, 2016|accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Mike Henriquez of [[Game Revolution]] favored the visual and artistic design, calling it \"top-notch\".<ref name=\"gamerevreview\"/> Sam White in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' commended id Software for ''Doom''{{'}}s delivery of performance on all platforms and praised the weapon design for ''Doom''{{'}}s continuity to introduce new weapons at a perfect speed so that gamers always play with something new and exciting.<ref name=ttreview>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/what-to-play/doom-review/|title=''Doom'' is a fiendishly moreish, impeccably refined shooter - review|first=Sam|last=White|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|date=May 23, 2016|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]{{'}}s Arthur Gies remarked positively upon the exploration for collectables and secrets, and their relevance to the new upgrade feature, but he was critical of instances where the game would lock away sections of a level without warning.<ref name=\"polygonreview\"/> Zack Furniss of [[Destructoid]] was originally skeptical regarding the \"glory kills\" feature, as were other critics, fearing that they might distract from the fast-paced gameplay. He ultimately considered them to fit well in the flow of gameplay that keeps players in the middle of combat without a slowed pace.<ref name=\"destructoidreview\"/> [[Giant Bomb]]{{'}}s Brad Shoemaker felt that the glory kills' generating small amounts of health and armor \"makes them an essential part of the give-and-take of ''Doom''{{'}}s super fast combat; do you dart into the fray for a glory kill to get a little health back, and risk getting mobbed by all the other enemies around?\"<ref name=\"giantbombreview\"/> Conversely, Kyle Orland of [[Ars Technica]] felt that the glory kills' briefly taking control away from the player can easily disorient players or misposition them, finding them hard to ignore for players that choose not to use them.<ref name=\"arstechreview\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/05/doom-2016-single-player-review-back-to-basics/|title=Doom (2016) single-player review: Back to basics|last=Orland|first=Kyle|publisher=[[Ars Technica]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe SnapMap mode was also positively received with ''Hardcore Gamer''{{'s}} Jordan Helm's noting the possibilities yet simplicity with its use, calling it an \"admirable feat\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2016/05/17/review-doom/207490/|title=Doom Review (PS4)|last=Helm|first=Jordan|work=Hardcore Gamer|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Matt Peckham of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' thought that the mode added further value to the overall package of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4336416/doom-review/|title=Review: The New \u2018Doom\u2019 Serves Up a Brew of Nostalgia and Carnage|last=Peckham|first=Matt|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Matt Bertz of ''[[Game Informer]]'' commented upon the accessibility but criticized the lack of diverse settings and possible limitations when compared to a traditional community-based [[mod (video games)|mod]].<ref name=\"gameinformerreview\"/> James Davenport of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' compared it to the modification in the original games, which he views as one of the primary reasons why ''Doom'' is still a recognizable title. He was disappointed by the lack of mod support, though he nevertheless noted SnapMap for its simple use and variety of ideas already created by players.<ref name=\"pcgamerreview\"/>\n\nThe multiplayer mode, however, garnered a mixed reception from critics. IGN's Joab Gilory was less favorable toward the multiplayer, calling the overall game \"a tale of two very different shooters\", stating that multiplayer did not live up to the standard set by the single-player components and would not satisfy players.<ref name=\"IGN review\"/> Simon Miller of ''VideoGamer.com'' found the multiplayer to be only all right.<ref name=\"videogamer.comreview\"/> Matt Buchholtz of ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' criticized what he felt was the network's poor handling of latency, and failing to register on-target shots as hits in some instances while not in others.<ref name=\"egmreview\"/> Edwin Evans-Thirlwell of [[Eurogamer]] singled out the \"Warpath\" multiplayer mode as the most interesting of the match type, describing it as \"memorable\", while he regarded the other multiplayer modes as underdeveloped and underwhelming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-05-17-doom-review|title=Review: Doom's superb campaign makes up for underwhelming multiplayer in id Software's remarkable comeback.|last=Evans-Thirlwell |first=Edwin|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Julian Benson from [[Kotaku]] wrote that ''Doom''{{'}}s multiplayer was very similar to other modern games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/doom-the-kotaku-review-1777315801|title=Doom: The Kotaku Review|last=Benson|first=Julian|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> More positively, however, David Houghton of [[GamesRadar]] enjoyed the multiplayer for the fast pace yet quick decision-making needed to succeed, calling it \"endlessly playable, smart, brutal fun.\"<ref name=\"gamesradarreview\"/> ''Doom'' was placed 1st in the GamesRadar's list of top FPS games of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 25 best FPS games of all time |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-fps-games/ |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=February 18, 2017 |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\nIt was the second best-selling retail game in its week of release in the UK, behind ''[[Uncharted 4: A Thief's End]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2016-05-16-uncharted-beats-doom-to-uk-retail-number-one|title=Uncharted beats Doom to UK retail number one|first=Dan|last=Pearson|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> This was reported to be 67% more in its first week than the previous entry, ''Doom 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-uncharted-4-has-strongest-debut-in/1100-6439822/|title=Top 10 UK Sales: Uncharted 4 Has Strongest Debut in Series History|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref> ''Doom'' was the second best-selling retail video game in the US in May 2016, also behind ''Uncharted 4''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/06/09/uncharted-4-leads-strong-month-of-software-sales-in-may-npd.aspx?|title=Uncharted 4 Leads Strong Month Of Software Sales In May NPD|first=Matt|last=Miller|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> By the end of May 2016, ''Doom''{{'}}s sales on the PC reached 500,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94944/doom-sales-reach-over-500k-on-pc-alone|title=''Doom'' sales reach over 500k on PC alone|first=Daniel|last=Perez|publisher=[[Shacknews]]|date=May 31, 2016|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The following month, by late June 2016, the game rose to number one in the UK charts, overtaking ''Uncharted 4'' and the later-released ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/431673/Charts+Doom+shoots+down+Overwatch/|title=Charts: Doom shoots down Overwatch|first=Chris|last=Martin|work=Game Reactor|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> and remained number one for a second week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-chart-doom-remains-no1/1100-6441268/|title=Top 10 UK Sales Chart: Doom Remains No.1|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> The game had surpassed one million sold copies for PCs in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=DOOM Sells 1 Million Copies on Steam|url=http://techdrake.com/2016/08/doom-sells-1-million-copies-steam/|publisher=Techdrake|date=August 11, 2016}}</ref> By July 2017, the game reached two million copies sold on PC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wholesgame.com/news/doom-sells-2-million-copies-on-pc/|title=Doom sells 2 million copies on PC|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dualshockers.com/doom-surpasses-2-million-copies-sold-steam/|title=DOOM Surpasses 2 Million Copies Sold on Steam|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref> In November 2017 ''Doom'' was the fourth best-selling Switch game, during its debut week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/11/sonic_forces_on_switch_has_solid_uk_launch_as_doom_moves_up_the_charts|title=Sonic Forces on Switch Has Solid UK Launch as DOOM Moves Up the Charts|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=March 5, 2018|website=[[Nintendo Life]]}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Doom'' was featured in multiple lists by critics and media outlets as one of the best games of 2016, being featured in game of the year lists and articles including [[Giant Bomb]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/articles/giant-bombs-2016-game-of-the-year-awards-day-five/1100-5525/|title = Giant Bomb's 2016 Game of the Year Awards: Day Five |first=| last=| date=December 30, 2016| accessdate=January 1, 2016| work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> GameSpot,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/game-of-the-year-2016-countdown-10-6/1100-6446349/|title=GameSpot's Game of the Year 2016 Countdown: 10 - 6|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=December 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> GamesRadar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/best-games-2016/3/|title=GamesRadar+'s Game of the Year 2016|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=December 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[The Escapist (website)|The Escapist]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/17359-The-Escapist-Game-of-the-Year-2016#&gid=gallery_6734&pid=1|title=The Escapist's 2016 Game of the Year|work=[[The Escapist (website)|The Escapist]]|publisher=[[Defy Media]]|date=January 1, 2017|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[The A.V. Club]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/our-favorite-games-2016-part-1-247166|title=Our favorite games of 2016, part 1 |work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=December 21, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> ''Rock, Paper, Shotgun'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/12/13/best-fps-2016-doom/|title=RPS 2016 Advent Calendar, Dec 13th: DOOM|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[Jim Sterling]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejimquisition.com/the-jimquisition-game-of-the-year-awards-2016/|title=The Jimquisition Game Of The Year Awards 2016|work=Jimquisition|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[VG247]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/12/26/vg247-games-of-the-year-awards-part-1-the-obvious-picks-were-not-even-sorry-for/|title=VG247 Games of the Year Awards, part 1: The Obvious Picks We\u2019re Not Even Sorry For|work=[[VG247]]|date=December 26, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> [[Daily Mirror]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/games-year-2016-best-video-9442676|title=Games of the Year 2016: The best video games this year, from Pok\u00e9mon GO to DOOM|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=December 31, 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> [[Zero Punctuation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/zero-punctuation/116977-Best-and-Worst-Games-of-2016|title=Best and Worst Games of 2016 &#124; Zero Punctuation Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist|website=www.escapistmagazine.com}}</ref> and [[Shacknews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/98296/game-of-the-year-2016-1-doom|title=Game of the Year 2016 #1: Doom|work=[[Shacknews]]|publisher=GamerHub|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Game Critics Awards]] 2015\n| Best Action Game\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/articles/best-of-e3-2015-game-critics-awards-announced/1100-5234/|title='Best of E3 2015' Game Critics Awards Announced|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Giant Bomb]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best PC Game\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2016\n|rowspan=\"4\" | [[Golden Joystick Award]] 2016\n| Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/ |title = Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public |first=Sam| last=Loveridge| date=September 15, 2016| accessdate=November 18, 2016| work=[[Digital Spy]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Visual Design\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| PC Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[The Game Awards 2016]]\n| Game of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{c