{"title_page": "Organizational studies", "text_new": "{{About|the discipline|the journal|Organization Studies (journal)}}\n'''Organizational studies''' is \"the examination of how individuals construct [[organizational structure]]s, processes, and practices and how these, in turn, shape social relations and create institutions that ultimately influence people\".<ref>Stewart Clegg, James Russell Bailey, ''International Encyclopedia of Organization Studies'' [http://www.sage-ereference.com/abstract/organization/d7.xml], Sage Publications, 2008</ref> \n\nOrganizational studies comprise different areas that deal with the different aspects of the organizations, many of the approaches are [[Structural functionalism|functionalist]] but [[Critical theory|critical research]] also provide alternative frame for understanding in the field. Fundamental to the study of management is organizational change.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suddaby|first=Roy|last2=Foster|first2=William M.|date=2017-01-01|title=History and Organizational Change|journal=Journal of Management|language=en|volume=43|issue=1|pages=19\u201338|doi=10.1177/0149206316675031|issn=0149-2063|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\nWith the recent historical turn, there is growing interest in historical organization studies, promising a closer union between organizational and historical research whose validity derives from historical veracity and conceptual rigor, enhancing understanding of historical, contemporary and future-directed social realities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maclean|first=Mairi|last2=Harvey|first2=Charles|last3=Clegg|first3=Stewart R.|date=2016-10-01|title=Conceptualizing Historical Organization Studies|url=http://amr.aom.org/content/41/4/609|journal=Academy of Management Review|language=en|volume=41|issue=4|pages=609\u2013632|doi=10.5465/amr.2014.0133|issn=0363-7425}}</ref>\nIt is the basic elementation of management\n\n==Subfields==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Organizational behavior]]\n* [[Organizational culture]]\n* [[Organizational ecology]]\n* [[Organizational learning]]\n* [[Organizational psychology]]\n* [[Organizational theory]]\n\n}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Organizational studies }}\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields of sociology]]\n[[Category:Organizational studies| ]]\n\n{{Sociology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the discipline|the journal|Organization Studies (journal)}}\n'''Organizational studies''' is \"the examination of how individuals construct [[organizational structure]]s, processes, and practices and how these, in turn, shape social relations and create institutions that ultimately influence people\".<ref>Stewart Clegg, James Russell Bailey, ''International Encyclopedia of Organization Studies'' [http://www.sage-ereference.com/abstract/organization/d7.xml], Sage Publications, 2008</ref> \n\nOrganizational studies comprise different areas that deal with the different aspects of the organizations, many of the approaches are [[Structural functionalism|functionalist]] but [[Critical theory|critical research]] also provide alternative frame for understanding in the field. Fundamental to the study of management is organizational change.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suddaby|first=Roy|last2=Foster|first2=William M.|date=2017-01-01|title=History and Organizational Change|journal=Journal of Management|language=en|volume=43|issue=1|pages=19\u201338|doi=10.1177/0149206316675031|issn=0149-2063|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\nWith the recent historical turn, there is growing interest in historical organization studies, promising a closer union between organizational and historical research whose validity derives from historical veracity and conceptual rigor, enhancing understanding of historical, contemporary and future-directed social realities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maclean|first=Mairi|last2=Harvey|first2=Charles|last3=Clegg|first3=Stewart R.|date=2016-10-01|title=Conceptualizing Historical Organization Studies|url=http://amr.aom.org/content/41/4/609|journal=Academy of Management Review|language=en|volume=41|issue=4|pages=609\u2013632|doi=10.5465/amr.2014.0133|issn=0363-7425}}</ref>\n\n==Subfields==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Organizational behavior]]\n* [[Organizational culture]]\n* [[Organizational ecology]]\n* [[Organizational learning]]\n* [[Organizational psychology]]\n* [[Organizational theory]]\n\n}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Organizational studies }}\n[[Category:Interdisciplinary subfields of sociology]]\n[[Category:Organizational studies| ]]\n\n{{Sociology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ParasYadav181818", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organizational_studies"}
{"title_page": "The Owl House (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|Disney animated TV series, 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Owl House\n| image                    = The Owl House intro.png\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Comedy]]<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" />\n*[[Fantasy]]<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" />\n}}\n| creator                  = Dana Terrace\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| voices                   = Sarah-Nicole Robles<br>[[Wendie Malick]]<br>[[Alex Hirsch]]\n| composer                 = T.J. Hill<ref>{{cite tweet|user=DanaTerrace|first=Dana|last=Terrace|date=July 19, 2019|number=1152331341876215809|title=I\u2019m going to give a full credits list for the Main Titles soon but just wanted to give a special shout out to @tjhill for composing a ROCKIN theme song, can\u2019t wait for you guys to hear what he\u2019s doing for the show. So lucky to have him as our composer!!!|access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 10\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = Dana Terrace\n| producer                 = Wade Wisinski<br>Stephen Sandoval (supervising producer)\n| editor                   = Kevin Locarro<br>Jenny Jordan (assistant editor)<br>Rachel Vine (story editor)\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[Disney Television Animation]]\n| distributor              = [[Disney-ABC Domestic Television]]\n| network                  = [[Disney Channel]]<br />[[Disney XD]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| website                  = https://disneynow.go.com/shows/the-owl-house/\n| website_title            = Official website\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| channel                  = \n| first_aired              = January 10, 2020\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Owl House''''' is an American animated fantasy-comedy television series produced by [[Disney Television Animation]]. The series was created by Dana Terrace, and premiered on [[Disney Channel]] on January 10, 2020.<ref name=DisneyABCPress>{{cite web|url=https://www.disneyabcpress.com/disneychannel/shows/the-owl-house/|title=The Owl House {{!}} Disney Channel Press|publisher=DisneyABC Press|access-date=March 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT-trailer\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Disney Channel|title=New York Comic-Con Sneak Peek! {{!}} The Owl House {{!}} Disney Channel|url= https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=JC3TiGmIwdY|website=YouTube|date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, the show was renewed for a second season in advance of the first season's premiere.<ref name=\"S2\" />\n\n==Plot==\nLuz is a teenage human girl who accidentally stumbles upon a portal to another world instead of going to Reality Check Camp. When on the Boiling Isles, which is made from the remains of a dead Titan, she befriends the rebellious witch Eda the Owl Lady and an adorable demon warrior named King. Despite not having [[Magic (supernatural)|magical]] abilities and having to pose as a witch due to the prejudice towards humans, Luz pursues her dream of becoming a witch by serving as Eda's apprentice at the Owl House and ultimately finds a new family in an unlikely setting.<ref name=Deadline2018>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/disney-channel-renews-star-vs-the-forces-of-evil-announces-amphibia-owl-house-1202300438/|title=Disney Channel Launching Toon Series 'Amphibia' & 'The Owl House', Renews 'Star Vs. The Forces Of Evil' For Season 4|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* Sarah-Nicole Robles as Luz Noceda,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wdtvpress.com/disneychannel/pressrelease/owl-house-s1-fact-sheet/|title=Owl House: S1 Fact Sheet|website=Disney ABC Press|date=November 21, 2019|access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Disney Channel|title=Official Trailer \ud83c\udfa5 {{!}} The Owl House {{!}} Disney Channel|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1W1FFiT51lg|website=YouTube|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> a 14-year-old [[Dominican-American]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elderkin |first1=Beth |title=The Personal Story Behind Owl House's Magical New Disney Heroine |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-personal-story-behind-owl-houses-magical-new-disney-1839128407 |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |work=[[io9]] |date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> girl who ends up on the Boiling Isles and becomes both Eda's apprentice and a new exchange student at Hexside Academy. Luz loves all things fantasy and magical, wishing to become a witch.<ref name=\"S2\" />\n* [[Wendie Malick]] as Edalyn \"Eda\" Clawthorne,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> the most powerful witch on the Boiling Isles, Luz's teacher, and a [[Bounty (reward)|wanted criminal]] for selling human items and not joining a coven.<ref name=\"S2\" /> Her nickname \"the Owl Lady\" comes from the fact that she was cursed to become an owl-like monster when she was younger by an unknown figure, which can only be countered by a daily elixir, which is gradually losing its effect on her as she revealed the curse is getting stronger as time passes. In mid-season finale, the elixir has lost its effect altogether due to the curse having grown too powerful. It can no longer cure her, much to her shock and fear.\n* [[Alex Hirsch]] as King,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a small dog-like demon warrior and Eda's roommate who is the self-proclaimed King of Demons.\n** Hirsch also voices Hooty, the witty sentient [[barn owl]]-headed [[doorknocker]] of the titular house.<ref name=\"S2\" />\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Tati Gabrielle]] as Willow,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a student at Hexside and Luz and Gus\u2019s friend who can do plant magic. Originally, Willow was placed in the abomination class until her use of plant magic caused her to be transferred to the plant class.\n* [[Issac Ryan Brown]] as Gus,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a student at Hexside and Luz and Willow\u2019s friend who can do illusion magic. He once led a human-appreciation club called the Human Appreciation Society before he was removed from the position by Principal Bump after what happened to the detention room.\n* [[Mae Whitman]] as Amity Blight,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a top student at Hexside who is an abomination expert and Luz's rival.\n* [[Bumper Robinson]] as Hieronymus Bump,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> the principal of Hexside who wears a demon-shaped hat over half his face.\n* [[JB Blanc]] as Professor Abominable, a teacher who teaches students how to make abominations and is carried around Hexside by his own Abomination.\n* Dana Terrace as Tiny Nose, a small round creature with a prominent nose.\n* [[Cissy Jones]] as Lilith Clawthorne, Eda's sister and leader of the Emperor's Coven.\n* [[Parvesh Cheena]] as Tiblit Tibley \"Tibbles\" Grimhammer III,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a night market stand owner who supplies Eda's curse elixir.\n* [[Eden Riegel]] as Boscha,<ref name=\"CharacterNames\" /> a three-eyed witch who is Amity's friend and is obsessed with Penstagram.\n* [[Isabella Rossellini]] as the Bat Queen, a former palisman formerly owned by a giant that takes care of other forgotten palismans and her kids.\n\n===Guest===\n*[[Matthew Rhys]]<ref name=\"S2\" />\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2020)===\n\n{{Episode table\n| background      =  #FADA5E\n| overall         = \n| season          = \n| title           = \n| titleR          = \n| airdate         = \n| DirectedBy      =\n| WrittenBy       =\n| airdateR        = \n| aux2=\n| aux2T=Storyboarded by\n| prodcode        = \n| prodcodeR       = <ref name=\"WDTV Press Episode Info\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.wdtvpress.com/disneychannel/shows/the-owl-house/episodes/ |title=WDTV Press Episode Info|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| viewers         =\n| country         = U.S.\n| episodes        =\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = A Lying Witch and a Warden\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|10}}\n| DirectedBy      = Stephen Sandoval\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Zach Marcus, John Bailey Owen, Dana Terrace & Rachel Vine|t=Terrace & Vine}}\n| Aux2            = Bosook \"Bo\" Coburn, Cat Harman-Mitchell, Sandoval & Terrace\n| ProdCode        = 101\n| Viewers         = 0.61<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-1-10-2020.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Friday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 1.10.2020 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Luz Noceda, a girl who loves fantasy, is forced by her mother Camilia (Elizabeth Grullon) to go to Reality Check Camp, following three different incidents at school that were brought to Camilia's attention. While waiting to be picked up, an owl takes her favorite witch book and she chases it into an abandoned house that transports her to the Boiling Isles, a magical realm in another dimension. She meets Eda, a fugitive witch who sells human items. Eda takes Luz to her home, the Owl House, where she introduces her to the adorably feisty King. Eda promises to take Luz back home if she helps them get King's crown back from Warden Wrath ([[Roger Craig Smith]]) at his prison, the Conformatorium. They successfully break in where Luz discovers that the \"crown\" is a kid's meal crown. Wrath captures them with the intent to ask Eda out on a date, but she refuses. A fight breaks out with Luz releasing the prisoners (whose crimes were for being different) and together defeat Wrath and escape. Luz decides to stay to become a witch and Eda reluctantly accepts. As Luz settles in for the night, she texts her mother to inform her that she's gonna like it at \"camp.\"\n| LineColor       = FADA5E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Witches Before Wizards\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|17}}\n| DirectedBy      = Stu Livingston\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Dana Terrace & Rachel Vine|t=Vine}}\n| Aux2            = Charlie Bryant, Hayley Foster & Cat Harman-Mitchell\n| ProdCode        = 102\n| Viewers         = 0.43<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-1-17-2020.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Friday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 1.17.2020 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Luz prepares herself to be a witch's apprentice, but is disappointed when a very indifferent Eda shows up to give her a simple task of delivering her potions to various customers. King goes with her as Luz is quick to learn that Bonesborough, the city on the Boiling Isles, is full of rather nasty creatures who do not care for her human background. Luz and King come across the brightly lit castle of a kindly wizard named Adegast ([[Robin Atkin Downes]]) who believes that Luz is the \"Chosen One\" who must retrieve the Celestial Staff. When Luz shows the map given to her by Adegast to Eda and King, they laugh at her. She leaves on her own for the quest just as Eda becomes suspicious and discovers the whole quest to be a ruse. Luz goes on her quest making allies while Eda and King follow behind. Eventually, Adegast is revealed to be a horrible [[puppeteer]] creature who used Luz to get capture Eda. He tries to coerce Luz into having her fantasy, but she breaks free with Eda and King helping her. Adegast is defeated and Eda eats him. Afterwards, Eda tells Luz that she must make her own destiny and shows her the surprising beauty of the Boiling Isles.\n| LineColor       = FADA5E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = I Was a Teenage Abomination\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|24}}\n| DirectedBy      = Stephen Sandoval\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Charley Feldman, Zach Marcus, Manuel Jesse Nieto Jr., John Bailey Owen, Dana Terrace & Rachel Vine |t=Owen & Terrace}}\n| Aux2            = Inbal Breda, Bosook \"Bo\" Coburn, Madeleine Flores, Chris Pianka & Sandoval\n| ProdCode        = 103\n| Viewers         = 0.45<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-1-24-2020.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Friday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 1.24.2020 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Luz is dissatisfied with how Eda handles \"training\" her, but perks up upon learning that there is a school that teaches magic called Hexside Academy of Magic and Demonics, something Eda is against as she dropped out. Luz meets Willow ([[Tati Gabrielle]]), a young witch who is picked on by top student Amity Blight ([[Mae Whitman]]) for being terrible at creating abominations. Luz decides to pretend to be her abomination so that she can give Willow a passing grade and so she can see the school where she also meets Gus ([[Issac Ryan Brown]]), a human-obsessed student. Luz is able to fool the class' teacher ([[JB Blanc]]) with her appearance. Meanwhile, Eda and King make a bet to see who makes the better teacher with King winning due to Luz having gone missing. However, King's \"student\", a slug named Prince Jr., attacks the pair forcing King to rely on Eda once again. Amity figures out that Luz is not an abomination and calls upon Principal Bump ([[Bumper Robinson]]) to examine her through dissection. Gus creates a diversion and a chase ensues ending with Willow showing her true gift in plant magic. Luz escapes to get help from Eda. Willow and Gus arrive where Luz learns that Willow's been exonerated as Bump puts her in the plant courses. However, Gus informs Luz that she's banned from the school, but he and Willow can teach her what they learned. However Luz happily accepts Eda as her teacher.\n| LineColor       = FADA5E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = The Intruder\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|31}}\n| DirectedBy      = Stu Livingston\n| WrittenBy       = Manuel Jesse Nieto Jr., Dana Terrace & Rachel Vine\n| Aux2            = Charlie Bryant, Cat Harman-Mitchell & Livingston\n| ProdCode        = 104\n| Viewers         = 0.51<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-1-31-2020.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Friday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 1.31.2020 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = King tries to teach Luz about demons. But when a boiling rainstorm rolls in, Luz takes the opportunity to get Eda to teach her some magic. Tired and wanting the light-up pen, Eda teaches Luz how to create light, which causes her to pass out. King tells Luz that Eda keeps a bottle of elixir in her room and believes it can give her magic. Before she drinks it however, a monster breaks into the house which King is convinced is the Snaggleback. He meets a real Snaggleback, which turns out to be a pathetic pink monkey wearing a shell. With Luz, King discover that the elixir was to prevent a curse from taking hold of Eda who is the real monster. With King's encouragement, Luz learns how to create light and uses it to sequester Eda and give her the elixir. Eda reveals that she was cursed when she was younger and it causes her to transform into an owl monster, hence her nickname \"The Owl Lady\". She tells them not to worry about it and compliments Luz's new ability. Eda later has a brief nightmare of a shadowy figure who cursed her, but wakes up before she can get answers. King is left to edit the information about the Snaggleback.\n| LineColor       = FADA5E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Covention\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|7|}}\n| DirectedBy      = Aminder Dhaliwal & Stu Livingston\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Charley Feldman, Zach Marcus, Manuel Jesse Nieto Jr., John Bailey Owen, Dana Terrace & Rachel Vine|t=Feldman, Terrace & Vine}}\n| Aux2            = Bosook \"Bo\" Coburn, Dhaliwal, Amelia Lorenz & Kelsey Norden\n| ProdCode        = 105\n| Viewers         = 0.51<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-2-7-2020.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Friday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 2.7.2020 {{!}} Showbuzz Daily|website=www.showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Luz learns about the \"Covention\", a convention for witch hopefuls and begs a reluctant Eda to take her. While there, Luz runs into Amity who mocks King. Angered, Luz challenges her to a witch's duel. If she wins, Amity must apologize to King and say humans can become witches. If Amity wins, Luz must give up her witch training which they seal with a binding circle. Eda runs into her estranged sister Lilith, leader of the Emperor's Coven and they learn about their respective proteges' deal. Realizing that Luz does not know enough magic, Eda decides to cheat. Amity discovers this, but Eda realizes that Lilith cheated as well, humiliating Amity and resulting in the sisters fighting, though Eda escapes. After talking with Luz and reaching an understanding, Amity calls off the binding circle to let her continue training. Lilith gets a call from Emperor Bellows' assistant Kikimora ([[Mela Lee]]) reminding her that she needs to capture Eda to receive her end of an unspecified deal.\n| Lin