{"title_page": "Howard Da Silva", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Howard Da Silva\n| image       = HowardDaSilva.jpg\n| caption     = Howard Da Silva, as Benjamin Franklin, in ''[[1776 (film)|1776]]'' (1972)\n| birth_name  = Howard Silverblatt\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1909|5|4|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1986|2|16|1909|5|4|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Actor, singer\n| yearsactive = 1930\u20131984\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Jane Taylor <br>|1936|1948|end=divorced}}<br> {{marriage|[[Marjorie Nelson]]<br>|1949|1960|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Nancy Nutter<br>|1961}}\n}}\n\n'''Howard Da Silva''' (born '''Howard Silverblatt''', May 4, 1909 \u2013 February 16, 1986) was an American actor, director and musical performer on stage, film, television and radio.  He was cast in dozens of productions on the New York stage, appeared in more than two dozen television programs, and acted in more than fifty feature films. Adept at both drama and musicals on the stage, he originated the role of Jud Fry in the original 1943 run of the [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] musical ''[[Oklahoma!]]'', and also portrayed the prosecuting attorney in the 1957 stage production of ''Compulsion''.  Da Silva was nominated for a 1960 [[Tony Award]] as Best Featured Actor in a Musical for his work in ''[[Fiorello!]]'', a musical about [[New York City]] mayor [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia|LaGuardia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1960 Tony Award\u00ae Best Featured Actor in a Musical|url=http://ibdb.com/person.php?id=67218#tabs-2|publisher=IBDB|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>  In 1961, Da Silva directed ''[[Purlie|Purlie Victorious]]'', by [[Ossie Davis]].\n\nMany of his early feature films were of the [[Film noir|noir]] genre in which he often played villains, such as Eddie Harwood in ''[[The Blue Dahlia]]'' and the sadistic Captain Francis Thompson in ''[[Two Years Before the Mast (film)|Two Years Before the Mast]]'' (both 1946). Da Silva's characterization of historic figures are among some of his most notable work: he was Lincoln's brawling friend Jack Armstrong in both play (1939) and film (1940) versions of ''[[Abe Lincoln in Illinois (film)|Abe Lincoln in Illinois]]'' written by [[Robert E. Sherwood|Robert Sherwood]]; [[Benjamin Franklin]] in the 1969\u20131972 stage musical ''[[1776 (musical)|1776]]'' and a reprisal of the role for the 1972 [[1776 (film)|film version]] of the production; Soviet leader [[Nikita Khrushchev]] in ''[[The Missiles of October]]'' (1974); [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in ''[[The Private Files of J. Edgar Hoover]]'' (1977); and [[Louis B. Mayer]] in ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'' (1981).\n\nDa Silva's American television character work included the defense attorney representing the robot in  ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' episode \"[[I, Robot (1964 The Outer Limits)|I, Robot]]\" (1964), and district attorney Anthony Cleese in ''[[For the People (1965 TV series)|For the People]]'' (1965).  For his performance as Eddie in the ''[[Great Performances]]'' production of ''Verna: USO Girl'' (1978), the actor received a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Comedy or Drama Special.<ref>{{cite web|title=1978 Prime Time Emmy Awards|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/howard-da-silva|publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Da Silva appeared in 26 episodes of the radio series, the ''[[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDa Silva was born in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], the son of Bertha (n\u00e9e Sen) and Benjamin Silverblatt, a dress cutter. His parents were both [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]]-speaking Jews born in [[Russia]]. His mother was a women's-rights activist.<ref name=NYobit>{{cite news|title=Howard Da Silva Dies at 76: Actor, Director and Author|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/02/18/obituaries/howard-da-silva-dies-at-76-actor-director-and-author.html|accessdate=February 21, 2015|work=February 18, 1986|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Before beginning his acting career on the [[theatre|stage]], he was employed as a steelworker.\n\nDa Silva was a graduate of the [[Carnegie Institute of Technology]] and studied acting with [[Eva Le Gallienne]] beginning in 1928 at the Civic Repertory Theatre.<ref name=NYobit/> He changed his surname to the Portuguese [[Da Silva]] (the name is sometimes misspelled '''Howard De Silva''').<ref>Room (2010), p. 134</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Cradle-Mercury-1.jpg|thumb|left|[[Marc Blitzstein]], Howard Da Silva and Olive Stanton in the [[Mercury Theatre]] production of ''[[The Cradle Will Rock]]'' (1938)]]\nDa Silva appeared in a number of [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theater|musicals]], including the role of Larry Foreman in the legendary first production of [[Marc Blitzstein]]'s musical, ''[[The Cradle Will Rock]]'' (1938).<ref name=182183Suskin/>  Later, he costarred in the original 1943 stage production of [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s ''[[Oklahoma!]]'', playing the role of the psychopathic Jud Fry.  He was the easygoing Ben Marino who opposed [[Tammany Hall]] in the Pulitzer winning musical ''[[Fiorello!]]''.\n\n[[File:Nixon 1776 play C3006-34.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Da Silva and other cast members of ''[[1776 (musical)|1776]]'' with [[Richard Nixon]] following a performance of the Tony Award-winning musical in the East Room of the White House (1971)]]\n\nIn 1969, Da Silva originated the role of [[Benjamin Franklin]] in the musical ''[[1776 (musical)|1776]]''. Four days before the show opened on Broadway, he suffered a minor [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] but refused to seek medical assistance because he wanted to make sure critics saw his performance.  After the four official critic performances were over, the cast left to go to the cast party and Da Silva went to the hospital and immediately took a leave of absence from the production.<ref>Peter Stone on the film DVD's audio commentary</ref>  While Da Silva recuperated, his understudy, [[Rex Everhart]], took over the role<ref name=\"linernotes\">{{Cite book|last = Kirkeby| first = Marc| title = 1776 Original Broadway Cast recording (liner notes)|page= 9| publisher = [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> and performed on the [[cast recording]]. Da Silva was able to reprise his role in the 1972 film version and appeared on that soundtrack album.\n\nDa Silva did summer stock at the [[Pine Brook Country Club]], located in the countryside of [[Nichols, Connecticut]], with the [[Group Theatre (New York)]] formed by [[Harold Clurman]], [[Cheryl Crawford]] and [[Lee Strasberg]] in the 1930s and early 1940s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pinewoodlake.org/ |title=Pinewood Lake website retrieved on 2010-09-10 |access-date=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727174723/http://www.pinewoodlake.org/ |archive-date=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>Images of America, Trumbull Historical Society, 1997, p. 123</ref>\n\nDa Silva appeared in over 60 [[film|motion pictures]]. Some of his memorable roles include a leading mutineer in ''[[The Sea Wolf (1941 film)|The Sea Wolf]]'' (1941), playing [[Ray Milland]]'s bartender in ''[[The Lost Weekend (film)|The Lost Weekend]]'' (1945), and the half-blind criminal \"Chicamaw 'One-Eye' Mobley\" in ''[[They Live by Night]]'' (1949).  He also released an album on [[Monitor Records (New York)|Monitor Records]] (MP 595) of political songs and ballads entitled ''Politics and Poker''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviews and Ratings of New Albums|journal=Billboard|date=October 21, 1960|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PSAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Politics+and+Poker+%22Howard+Da+Silva%22#v=onepage&q=Politics%20and%20Poker%20%22Howard%20Da%20Silva%22&f=false|accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDa Silva returned to the stage, and was nominated for the 1960 [[Tony Award]] for Best Featured Actor in a Musical for his role as \"Ben Marino\" in ''[[Fiorello!]]'' (1959). After being blacklisted, Da Silva and Nelson left Los Angeles for New York to perform in ''The World of Sholom Aleichem''.<ref>Frommer, Frommer (2014), p. 82</ref>\n\nDa Silva was nominated for the British [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA Film Award]] for Best Foreign Actor for his performance as Dr. Swinford in ''[[David and Lisa]]'' (1962).<ref name=BAFTA>{{cite web|title=Foreign Actor in 1964|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/1964/film/foreign-actor|website=BAFTA Awards|publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref> Da Silva portrayed Soviet Premier Khrushchev in the television docudrama ''[[The Missiles of October]]'' (1974). He won the [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Comedy or Drama Special for his role as Eddie in ''[[Verna: U.S.O. Girl]]'' (1978) with [[Sissy Spacek]].\n\nDa Silva's TV guest appearances, after the era in which blacklisting was strongest, include such programs as ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'', ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'', ''[[Gentle Ben]]'', ''[[Mannix]]'', ''[[Love, American Style]]'', ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', and ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]''.\n\nDa Silva also played President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in ''[[The Private Files of J. Edgar Hoover]]'' (1977), Hollywood mogul [[Louis B. Mayer]] in ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'' (1981), and American statesman [[Benjamin Franklin]] in ''[[1776 (musical)|1776]]'' (1972), as well as a documentary depicting the life of Ben Franklin shown at Franklin's house in Philadelphia. He appeared in two different film adaptations of [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]]'s 1925 novel, ''[[The Great Gatsby]]''. In the [[The Great Gatsby (1949 film)|1949 production]] with [[Alan Ladd]] as Gatsby, Da Silva played garage owner George Wilson; in the [[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|1974 film]] with [[Robert Redford]], Da Silva was Meyer Wolfsheim, the flamboyant gambler with the interesting cufflinks. In his final appearance on screen, Da Silva played a New York photographer fascinated with the reclusive [[Greta Garbo]] in the film ''[[Garbo Talks]]'' (1984), directed by [[Sidney Lumet]].\n\nHe also did voice acting in 26 episodes of the popular 1974\u201382 radio thriller series ''[[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]]'' (between July 1974 and February 1977).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbsrmt.mousetrap.net/RMTdb/sp.php?id=hdasilva|title=CBS Radio Mystery Theater Database|accessdate=2008-05-10}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1978, he recorded linking narration for episodes of the British [[television program]] ''[[Doctor Who]]'' broadcast in the United States.\n\n==Blacklisting==\nDa Silva became one of hundreds of artists [[Hollywood blacklist|blacklisted]] in the entertainment industry during the [[House Committee on Unamerican Activities]] investigation into alleged [[communism|Communist]] influence in the industry. Following his March 1951 testimony in which he repeatedly invoked his [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] rights,<ref>Ryskind (2015), pp. 391\u2013393</ref> his lead performance in the completed feature film ''[[Slaughter Trail]]'' was re-shot with actor [[Brian Donlevy]].<ref name=146Humphries>Humphries (2010), p.146</ref> <!-- Requires support from reliable source or sources. --> Da Silva continued to find work on the New York stage, but did not work in feature films again until 1961 when he appeared in ''[[David and Lisa]]'' (a [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]-nominated performance).<ref name=BAFTA/><ref>Buhle, Wagner (2004), p. 291</ref>  He was eventually cleared of any charges in 1960,<ref>Ghiglione (2008), p. ebook</ref> but not before his career in television had also stalled, with no work between 1951 and 1959 when he appeared in ''[[The Play of the Week]]''. The brief respite was followed by another television career void until his appearance in a 1963 episode of [[The Defenders (1961 TV series)|''The Defenders'']]. That was the beginning of the end of Da Silva's blacklist, and the show's producer [[Herb Brodkin]] paired Da Silva with [[William Shatner]] when he created the television series [[For the People (1965 TV series)|''For the People'']].<ref>Shatner, Fisher (2008), pp. 95\u201396</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDa Silva married actress [[Marjorie Nelson]] in 1949.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/78/Howard-Da-Silva.html Biography at filmreference.com]</ref> Da Silva and Nelson divorced in 1960. He married twice more and had a total of two sons and three daughters.<ref name=NYobit/>\n\nDa Silva died of [[lymphoma]], aged 76, in [[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]].<ref name=NYobit/>\n\n==Acting credits==\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Stage work of Howard Da Silva\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Opening date\n! scope=\"col\"  class=\"unsortable\"|Closing date\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"  class=\"unsortable\"|Role\n! scope=\"col\"|Theatre\n! scope=\"col\"  class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n!scope=\"col\"  class=\"unsortable\"| Refs\n|-\n|  scope=\"row\"|Apr 21, 1930\n|May 1930\n|''[[Romeo and Juliet]]''\n|Apothecary\n|Civic Repertory Theatre\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Romeo and Juliet|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=11108|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"| Oct 6, 1930\n| unknown\n| {{sort|Green|''The Green Cockatoo''}}\n|Scaevola\n|Civic Repertory Theatre\n|Written in 1899 by Arthur Schnitzler as ''Der gr\u00fcne Kakadu''\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=The Green Cockatoo|url=http://www.ibdb.com/prod