re\n|Written by [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma!|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=1285|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>Suskin (2010), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|April 9, 1946\n|\n|''Shootin' Star''\n|Saloon proprietor, sheriff\n|Shubert Theatre, Philadelphia\n|Written by Walter Hart and Louis Jacobs\n|<ref>{{cite journal|title=Out-of-town-openings|journal=Billboard|date=April 20, 1946|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l0UEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT47&dq=old+time+radio+%22howard+da+silva%22#v=onepage&q=old%20time%20radio%20%22howard%20da%20silva%22&f=false}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"| Dec 26, 1947\n|Feb 7, 1948\n|{{sort|Cradle|''The Cradle Will Rock''}}\n|(directed)\n|[[Mansfield Theatre]], [[Broadway Theatre (53rd Street)|Broadway Theatre]]\n|Written by Marc Blitzstein\n|<ref name=182183Suskin/><ref>{{cite web|title=The Cradle Will Rock|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=1625|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"| Oct 18, 1950\n|Oct 28, 1950\n|''[[Burning Bright]]''\n|Friend Ed\n|Broadhurst Theatre\n|Written by [[John Steinbeck]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Burning Bright|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=1872|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Nov 23, 1954\n|Jan 2, 1955\n|''Sandhog''\n|(produced)\n|[[Phoenix Theatre (New York)|Phoenix Theatre]]\n| Written by [[Earl Robinson]] and [[Waldo Salt]], based on ''St. Columbia and the River'' by [[Theodore Dreiser]]. [[Rachel Productions]] was owned by da Silva and [[Arnold Perl]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandhog|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=395593|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Nov 4, 1956\n|Nov 25, 1956\n|''[[Enough Stupidity in Every Wise Man|Diary of a Scoundrel]]''\n|Neel Fedoseitch Mamaev\n|Phoenix Theatre\n|Written by [[Alexander Ostrovsky]]; adapted by [[Rodney Ackland]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Diary of a Scoundre|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=482220|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Oct 24, 1957\n|Feb 22, 1958\n|''Compulsion''\n|Horn The Prosecuting Attorney\n|[[Ambassador Theatre (New York City)|Ambassador Theatre]]\n|Based on the 1956 [[Meyer Levin]] novel of the same name; later produced as the 1959 film ''[[Compulsion (1959 film)|Compulsion]]''.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Compulsion|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=2651|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Nov 23, 1959\n|Oct 28, 1961\n|''[[Fiorello!]]''\n|Ben Marino\n|Broadhurst Theatre, Broadway Theatre\n|Based on the book by [[Jerome Weidman]] and [[George Abbott]];Da Silva nominated for 1960 [[Tony Award]] Best Featured Actor in a Musical\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Fiorello!|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=2798|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>Suskin (2010), p. 251</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Sept 28, 1961\n|May 13, 1962\n|''[[Purlie|Purlie Victorious]]''\n| (directed)\n|[[Cort Theatre]], [[Longacre Theatre]]\n|Written by [[Ossie Davis]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Purlie Victorious|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=2877|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>Rose (2001), pp. 162\u2013163</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Jan 10, 1962\n|Mar 10, 1962\n|''Romulus''\n|Ottaker\n|[[Music Box Theatre]]\n|Written by [[Friedrich Duerrenmatt]]; adapted by [[Gore Vidal]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Romulus|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=2761|website=IBDB|publisher=The Broadway League|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\"|Dec 12, 1962\n|Dec 15, 1962\n|''In the Counting House''\n|Max Hartman\n|[[Biltmore Theater]]\n|Written by Leslie Weiner